# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christopher-benfey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The American Revolutionary Period (1775–1783) is notable for the political writings of Benjamin Franklin, Alexander Hamilton, Thomas Paine, and Thomas Jefferson.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] An early novel is William Hill Brown's *The Power of Sympathy*, published in 1791.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Ralph Waldo Emerson pioneered the influential Transcendentalism movement; Henry David Thoreau, the author of *Walden*, was influenced by this movement.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The conflict surrounding abolitionism inspired writers, like Harriet Beecher Stowe, and authors of slave narratives, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Nathaniel Hawthorne's *The Scarlet Letter* (1850) explored the dark aspects of human nature, as did Herman Melville's *Moby-Dick* (1851).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Major American poets of the 19th century include Walt Whitman, Melville, and Emily Dickinson.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Mark Twain was the first major American writer to be born in the West.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Henry James achieved international recognition with novels like *The Portrait of a Lady* (1881).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Following World War I, modernist literature rejected nineteenth-century forms and values.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Scott Fitzgerald captured the carefree mood of the 1920s, while John Dos Passos and Ernest Hemingway, who became famous with *The Sun Also Rises* and *A Farewell to Arms*, and William Faulkner, adopted experimental forms.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] American modernist poets included diverse figures such as Wallace Stevens, T.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Great Depression–era writers included John Steinbeck, the author of *The Grapes of Wrath* (1939) and *Of Mice and Men* (1937).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] America's involvement in World War II led to works such as Norman Mailer's *The Naked and the Dead* (1948), Joseph Heller's *Catch-22* (1961) and Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s *Slaughterhouse-Five* (1969).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Prominent playwrights of these years include Eugene O'Neill, who won a Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the mid-twentieth century, drama was dominated by Tennessee Williams and Arthur Miller.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the late-20th and early-21st centuries, there has been increased popular and academic acceptance of literature written by immigrant, ethnic, and LGBTQ writers, and of writings in languages other than English.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Examples of pioneers in these areas include the LGBT author Michael Cunningham, the Asian American authors Maxine Hong Kingston and Ocean Vuong, and African American authors such as Ralph Ellison, James Baldwin, and Toni Morrison.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 2016, the folk-rock songwriter Bob Dylan won the Nobel Prize in Literature, and in 2020 the poet Louise Glück became the most recent American winner.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Oral literature and storytelling has existed among the various Indigenous tribes, prior to the arrival of European colonists.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The traditional territories of some tribes traverse national boundaries and such literature is not homogeneous but reflects the different cultures of these peoples.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1771 the first work by a Native American in English, *A Sermon Preached at the Execution of Moses Paul, an Indian*, by Samson Occom, from the Mohegan tribe, was published and went through 19 editions.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] A significant event in the development of Native American literature in English came with the awarding of the Pulitzer Prize in 1969 to N.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Scott Momaday (Kiowa tribe) for his novel *House Made of Dawn* (1968).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The Thirteen Colonies have often been regarded as the center of early American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] However, the first European settlements in North America had been founded elsewhere, many years earlier.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The first item printed in Pennsylvania was in German and was the largest book printed in any of the colonies before the American Revolution.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Spanish and French had two of the strongest colonial literary traditions in the areas that now comprise the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Moreover, a wealth of oral literary traditions existed on the continent among the numerous different Native American tribes.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] However, with the onset of English settlement of North America, the English language established a foothold in North America that would spread with the growth of England's political influence in the continent and the continued arrival of settlers from the British Isles.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] This included the English capture of the Dutch colony of New Amsterdam in 1664, with the English renaming it New York and changing the administrative language from Dutch to English.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] From 1696 to 1700, only about 250 separate items were issued from the major printing presses in the American colonies.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] This is a small number, compared to the output of the printers in London at the time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] London printers published materials written by New England authors, so, the body of American literature was larger than what was published in North America.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] However, printing was established in the American colonies before it was allowed in most of England.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In England, restrictive laws had long confined printing to four locations, where the government could monitor what was published: London, York, Oxford, and Cambridge.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Because of this, the colonies ventured into the modern world earlier than their provincial English counterparts.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Some American literature of the time consisted of pamphlets and writings extolling the benefits of the colonies to both a European and colonial audience.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Captain John Smith could be considered the first American author with his works *A True Relation of Such Occurrences and Accidents of Noate as Hath Happened in Virginia ...* (1608) and *The Generall Historie of Virginia, New England, and the Summer Isles* (1624).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other writers of this genre included Daniel Denton, Thomas Ashe, William Penn, George Percy, William Strachey, Daniel Coxe, Gabriel Thomas, and John Lawson.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The religious disputes that prompted settlement in America were important topics of early American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] A journal written by John Winthrop, *The History of New England*, discussed the religious foundations of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Edward Winslow also recorded a diary of the first years after the *Mayflower's* arrival.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] "A modell of Christian Charity" by John Winthrop, the first governor of Massachusetts, was a Sermon preached on the *Arbella* (the flagship of the Winthrop Fleet) in 1630.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] This work outlined the ideal society that he and the other Separatists would build, in an attempt to realize a "Puritan utopia".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other religious writers included Increase Mather and William Bradford, author of the journal published as a *History of Plymouth Plantation, 1620–47*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Others like Roger Williams and Nathaniel Ward more fiercely argued state and church separation.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Others, such as Thomas Morton, cared little for the church; Morton's *The New English Canaan* mocked the Puritans and declared that the local Native Americans were better people than them.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other late writings described conflicts and interaction with the Indians, as seen in writings by Daniel Gookin, Alexander Whitaker, John Mason, Benjamin Church, and Daniel J.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] John Eliot translated the Bible into the Algonquin language (1663) as *Mamusse Wunneetupanatamwe Up-Biblum God*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] It was the first complete Bible printed in the Western hemisphere; Stephen Daye printed 1,000 copies on the first printing press in the American colonies.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Of the second generation of New England settlers, Cotton Mather stands out as a theologian and historian, who wrote the history of the colonies with a view to God's activity in their midst and to connecting the Puritan leaders with the great heroes of the Christian faith.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His best-known works include the *Magnalia Christi Americana* (1702), the *Wonders of the Invisible World* and *The Biblia Americana*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Jonathan Edwards and George Whitefield represented the Great Awakening, a religious revival in the early 18th century that emphasized Calvinist thought.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other Puritan and religious writers include Thomas Hooker, Thomas Shepard, John Wise, and Samuel Willard.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Less strict and serious writers included Samuel Sewall (who wrote a diary revealing the daily life of the late 17th century), and Sarah Kemble Knight (who likewise wrote a diary).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] New England was not the only area in the colonies with a literature: southern literature was also growing at this time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The diary of William Byrd, a planter, and his *The History of the Dividing Line* (1728) described the expedition to survey the swamp between Virginia and North Carolina but also comments on the differences between American Indians and the white settlers in the area.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In a similar book, *Travels through North and South Carolina, Georgia, East and West*, William Bartram described the Southern landscape and the Indian tribes he encountered; Bartram's book was popular in Europe, being translated into German, French and Dutch.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] As the colonies moved toward independence from Britain, an important discussion of American culture and identity came from the French immigrant J.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] This same period saw the beginning of African-American literature, through the poet Phillis Wheatley and the slave narrative of Olaudah Equiano, *The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano* (1789).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] At this time, American Indian literature also began to flourish.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Samson Occom published his *A Sermon Preached at the Execution of Moses Paul* and a popular hymnbook, *Collection of Hymns and Spiritual Songs*, "the first Indian best-seller".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The Revolutionary period also contained political writings, including those by colonists Samuel Adams, Josiah Quincy, John Dickinson, and Joseph Galloway, the last being a loyalist to the crown.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Two key figures were Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Paine.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Franklin's *Poor Richard's Almanack* and *The Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin* are esteemed works, with their wit and influence toward the formation of a budding American identity.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Paine's pamphlet *Common Sense* and *The American Crisis* writings are seen as playing a key role in influencing the political tone of the time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] During the American Revolutionary War, poems and songs such as "Nathan Hale" were popular.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Major satirists included John Trumbull and Francis Hopkinson.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Philip Morin Freneau also wrote poems about the War.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] During the 18th century, writing shifted from the Puritanism of Winthrop and Bradford to ideas of reason in the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The belief that human and natural occurrences were messages from God no longer fit with the budding anthropocentric culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Many intellectuals believed that the human mind could comprehend the universe through the laws of physics, as described by Isaac Newton.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The first book published in North America that promoted Newton and natural theology was Mather's *The Christian Philosopher* (1721).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The enormous scientific, economic, social, and philosophical, changes of the 18th century, called the Enlightenment, impacted the authority of clergyman and scripture, making way for democratic principles.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The increase in population helped account for the greater diversity of opinion in religious and political life, as seen in the literature of this time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1670, the population of the colonies numbered approximately 111,000.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Thirty years later, it was more than 250,000.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The growth of communities, and therefore social life, led people to become more interested in the progress of individuals and their shared experience in the colonies.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] These new ideas can be seen in the popularity of Benjamin Franklin's *Autobiography*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Even earlier than Franklin was Cadwallader Colden (1689–1776), whose book *The History of the Five Indian Nations*, published in 1727 was one of the first texts published on Iroquois history.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Colden also wrote a book on botany, which attracted the attention of Carl Linnaeus, and he maintained a long term correspondence with Franklin.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the post-war period, Thomas Jefferson established his place in American literature through his authorship of the Declaration of Independence, his influence on the U.S.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Constitution, his autobiography, his Notes on the State of Virginia, and his many letters.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The Federalist essays by Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and John Jay presented a significant historical discussion of American government organization and republican values.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Fisher Ames, James Otis, and Patrick Henry are also valued for their political writings and orations.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Early American literature struggled to find a unique voice in existing literary genre, and this tendency was reflected in novels.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] European styles were frequently imitated, but critics usually considered the imitations inferior.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, the first American novels were published.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] These fictions were too lengthy to be printed for public reading.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Publishers took a chance on these works in hopes they would become steady sellers and need to be reprinted.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] This scheme was ultimately successful because male and female literacy rates were increasing at the time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among the first American novels are Thomas Attwood Digges's *Adventures of Alonso*, published in London in 1775 and William Hill Brown's *The Power of Sympathy* published in 1789.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Brown's novel depicts a tragic love story between siblings who fell in love without knowing they were related.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the next decade, important women writers also published novels.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Susanna Rowson is best known for her novel *Charlotte: A Tale of Truth*, published in London in 1791.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1794 the novel was reissued in Philadelphia under the title, *Charlotte Temple*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *Charlotte Temple* is a seduction tale, written in the third person, which warns against listening to the voice of love and counsels resistance.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] She also wrote nine novels, six theatrical works, two collections of poetry, six textbooks, and countless songs.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Reaching more than a million and a half readers over a century and a half, *Charlotte Temple* was the biggest seller of the 19th century before Stowe's *Uncle Tom's Cabin*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Although Rowson was extremely popular in her time and is often acknowledged in accounts of the development of the early American novel, *Charlotte Temple* often is criticized as a sentimental novel of seduction.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Hannah Webster Foster's *The Coquette: Or, the History of Eliza Wharton* was published in 1797 and was extremely popular.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Told from Foster's point of view and based on the real life of Eliza Whitman, the novel is about a woman who is seduced and abandoned.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Eliza is a "coquette" who is courted by two very different men: a clergyman who offers her a comfortable domestic life and a noted libertine.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Unable to choose between them, she finds herself single when both men get married.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] She eventually yields to the artful libertine and gives birth to an illegitimate stillborn child at an inn.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *The Coquette* is praised for its demonstration of the era's contradictory ideas of womanhood. even as it has been criticized for delegitimizing protest against women's subordination.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Both *The Coquette* and *Charlotte Temple* are novels that treat the right of women to live as equals as the new democratic experiment.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] These novels are of the sentimental genre, characterized by overindulgence in emotion, an invitation to listen to the voice of reason against misleading passions, as well as an optimistic overemphasis on the essential goodness of humanity.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Sentimentalism is often thought to be a reaction against the Calvinistic belief in the depravity of human nature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] While many of these novels were popular, the economic infrastructure of the time did not allow these writers to make a living through their writing alone.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Charles Brockden Brown is the earliest American novelist whose works are still commonly read.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He published *Wieland* in 1798, and in 1799 published *Ormond*, *Edgar Huntly*, and *Arthur Mervyn*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The first writer to be able to support himself through the income generated by his publications alone was Washington Irving.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He completed his first major book in 1809 titled *A History of New-York from the Beginning of the World to the End of the Dutch Dynasty*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Of the picaresque genre, Hugh Henry Brackenridge published *Modern Chivalry* in 1792–1815; Tabitha Gilman Tenney wrote *Female Quixotism: Exhibited in the Romantic Opinions and Extravagant Adventure of Dorcasina Sheldon* in 1801; Royall Tyler wrote *The Algerine Captive* in 1797.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other notable authors include William Gilmore Simms, who wrote *Martin Faber* in 1833, *Guy Rivers* in 1834, and *The Yemassee* in 1835.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Lydia Maria Child wrote *Hobomok* in 1824 and *The Rebels* in 1825.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] John Neal wrote *Keep Cool* in 1817, *Logan* in 1822, *Seventy-Six* in 1823, *Randolph* in 1823, *Errata* in 1823, *Brother Jonathan* in 1825, and *Rachel Dyer* (earliest use of the Salem witch trials as the basis for a novel) in 1828.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Catherine Maria Sedgwick wrote *A New England Tale* in 1822, *Redwood* in 1824, *Hope Leslie* in 1827, and *The Linwoods* in 1835.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] James Kirke Paulding wrote *The Lion of the West* in 1830, *The Dutchman's Fireside* in 1831, and *Westward Ho!* in 1832.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Omar ibn Said, a Muslim slave in the Carolinas, wrote an autobiography in Arabic in 1831, considered an early example of African-American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Robert Montgomery Bird wrote *Calavar* in 1834 and *Nick of the Woods* in 1837.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] James Fenimore Cooper was a notable author best known for his novel *The Last of the Mohicans* written in 1826.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] George Tucker produced in 1824 the first fiction of Virginia colonial life with *The Valley of Shenandoah*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He followed in 1827 with one of the country's first science fictions: *A Voyage to the Moon: With Some Account of the Manners and Customs, Science and Philosophy, of the People of Morosofia, and Other Lunarians*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] After the War of 1812 against Britain, there was an increasing desire to produce a uniquely American literature and culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Literary figures who took up the cause included Washington Irving, William Cullen Bryant, and James Fenimore Cooper.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Irving wrote humorous works in *Salmagundi* and the satire *A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker* (1809).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Bryant wrote early romantic and nature-inspired poetry, which evolved away from their European origins.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Cooper's *Leatherstocking Tales* about Natty Bumppo (which includes *The Last of the Mohicans*, 1826) treated uniquely American material in ways that were popular both in the new country and Europe.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] John Neal as a critic played a key role in developing American literary nationalism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Edgar Allan Poe was born in Boston but raised in Virginia and identified with the Southern U.S.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1832, he began writing short stories, such as "The Masque of the Red Death", "The Pit and the Pendulum", and "The Fall of the House of Usher", that explore hidden depths of human psychology and push the boundaries of fiction.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Poe's "The Murders in the Rue Morgue", is seen as the first detective story.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Humorous writers were also popular and included Seba Smith and Benjamin Penhallow Shillaber in New England and Davy Crockett, Augustus Baldwin Longstreet, Johnson J.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Hooper, Thomas Bangs Thorpe, and George Washington Harris writing about the American frontier.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In New England, a group of writers known as Boston Brahmins included James Russell Lowell, then in later years Henry Wadsworth Longfellow and Oliver Wendell Holmes Sr.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1836, Ralph Waldo Emerson, who had renounced his ministry, published his essay *Nature*, which argued that men should dispense with organized religion and reach a lofty spiritual state by studying and interacting with the natural world.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He expanded his influence with his lecture "The American Scholar", delivered in Cambridge in 1837, which called upon Americans to create a uniquely American writing style.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Both the nation and the individual should declare independence.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Emerson's influence fostered the movement now known as Transcendentalism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among the leaders was Emerson's friend Henry David Thoreau, a nonconformist and critic of American commercial culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] After living mostly by himself for two years in a nearby cabin by a wooded pond, Thoreau wrote *Walden* (1854), a memoir that urges resistance to the dictates of society.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other Transcendentalists included Amos Bronson Alcott, Margaret Fuller, George Ripley, Orestes Brownson, and Jones Very.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] As one of the great works of the Revolutionary period was written by a Frenchman, so too was a work about America from this generation.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The French politician Alexis de Tocqueville's two-volume *Democracy in America* (1835 and 1840) described his travels through the young nation, making observations about the relations between American politics, individualism, and community.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The political conflict surrounding abolitionism inspired the writings of William Lloyd Garrison and his paper *The Liberator*, along with the poet John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe in her world-famous *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] These efforts were supported by the continuation of the slave narrative autobiography.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1837, the young Nathaniel Hawthorne (1804–1864) collected some of his stories as *Twice-Told Tales*, a volume rich in symbolism and occult incidents.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Hawthorne went on to write full-length "romances", quasi-allegorical novels that explore the themes of guilt, pride, and emotional repression.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His masterpiece, *The Scarlet Letter* (1850), is a drama, set in Puritan Massachusetts, about a woman cast out of her community for committing adultery with a minister who refuses to acknowledge his own sin.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Herman Melville (1819–1891) made a name for himself with *Typee* and *Omoo*, adventure tales based loosely on his own life at sea and jumping ship to live among South Sea natives.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Becoming a friend of Hawthorne's in 1850, Melville was inspired by his work.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *Moby-Dick* (1851) became not only an adventure tale about the pursuit of a white whale, but also an exploration of obsession, the nature of evil, and human struggle against the elements.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] It was a critical and commercial failure, as were his subsequent novels.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He turned to poetry and did not return to fiction until the short novel *Billy Budd, Sailor*, which he left unfinished at his death in 1891.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In it, Melville dramatizes the conflicting claims of duty and compassion on board a ship in time of war.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His more profound books sold poorly, and he had been long forgotten by the time of his death.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Anti-transcendental works from Melville, Hawthorne, and Poe all comprise the Dark romanticism sub-genre of popular literature at this time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Slave narrative autobiography from this period include Frederick Douglass's *Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave* (1845) and Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* (1861).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] At this time, American Indian autobiography develops, most notably in William Apess's *A Son of the Forest* (1829) and George Copway's *The Life, History and Travels of Kah-ge-ga-gah-bowh* (1847).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Moreover, minority authors were beginning to publish fiction, as in William Wells Brown's *Clotel; or, The President's Daughter* (1853), Frank J.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Webb's *The Garies and Their Friends*, (1857) Martin Delany's *Blake; or, The Huts of America* (1859–62) and Harriet E.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Wilson's *Our Nig: Sketches from the Life of a Free Black* (1859) as early African American novels, and John Rollin Ridge's *The Life and Adventures of Joaquín Murieta* (1854), which is considered the first American Indian novel but is also an early story that talks about Mexican-American issues.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Mark Twain (the pen name used by Samuel Langhorne Clemens, 1835–1910) was among the first major American writers to be born away from the East Coast – in the border state of Missouri.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His regional masterpieces were the memoir *Life on the Mississippi* and the novels *Adventures of Tom Sawyer* and *Adventures of Huckleberry Finn* (1884).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Twain's style – influenced by journalism, wedded to the vernacular, direct and unadorned but also highly evocative and irreverently humorous – changed the way Americans write their language.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His characters speak like real people and sound distinctively American, using local dialects, newly invented words, and regional accents.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other writers interested in regional differences and dialect were George W.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Cable, Thomas Nelson Page, Joel Chandler Harris, Mary Noailles Murfree (Charles Egbert Craddock), Sarah Orne Jewett, Mary E.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Wilkins Freeman, Henry Cuyler Bunner, and William Sydney Porter (O.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] A version of local color regionalism that focused on minority experiences can be seen in the works of Charles W.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Chesnutt (writing about African Americans), of María Ruiz de Burton, one of the earliest Mexican-American novelists to write in English, and in the Yiddish-inflected works of Abraham Cahan.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] William Dean Howells also represented the realist tradition through his novels, including *The Rise of Silas Lapham* (1885) and his work as editor of *The Atlantic Monthly*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Henry James (1843–1916) confronted the Old World-New World dilemma by writing directly about it.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Although he was born in New York City, James spent most of his adult life in England.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Many of his novels center on Americans who live in or travel to Europe.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] With its intricate, highly qualified sentences and dissection of emotional and psychological nuance.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His masterpieces include *Washington Square* (1880), *The Portrait of a Lady* (1881), *The Bostonians* (1886), *The Wings of the Dove* (1902), *The Ambassadors* (1903), and *The Golden Bowl* (1904).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Stephen Crane (1871–1900), best known for his American Civil War novel *The Red Badge of Courage* (1895), depicted the life of New York City prostitutes in *Maggie: A Girl of the Streets* (1893).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] And in *Sister Carrie* (1900), Theodore Dreiser (1871–1945) portrayed a country girl who moves to Chicago and becomes a kept woman.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Frank Norris's (1870–1902) fiction was predominantly in the naturalist genre.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His notable works include *McTeague: A Story of San Francisco* (1899), *The Octopus: A Story of California* (1901) and *The Pit* (1903).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Norris along with Hamlin Garland (1860–1940) wrote about the problems of American farmers and other social issues from a naturalist perspective.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Garland is best known for his fiction involving hard-working Midwestern farmers.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Edward Bellamy's utopian novel *Looking Backward* (1888) was concerned with political and social issues.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] At the beginning of the 20th century, American novelists were expanding fiction to encompass a broader range of experiences, and sometimes connected these to the naturalist school of realism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In her stories and novels, Edith Wharton (1862–1937) scrutinized the upper-class, Eastern-seaboard society in which she had grown up.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *The Age of Innocence* (1920) centers on a man who chooses to marry a conventional, socially acceptable woman rather than a fascinating outsider.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Social issues and the power of corporations was the central concern of some writers at this time.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Upton Sinclair (1878–1968), most famous for his muckraking novel *The Jungle* (1906), advocated socialism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Jack London (1876–1916) was also very committed to social justice and socialism through some of his books as *The Iron Heel* or *The People of the Abyss*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other political writers of the period included Edwin Markham (1852–1940) and William Vaughn Moody.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Tarbell and Lincoln Steffens, were labeled "The Muckrakers".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Henry Brooks Adams's literate autobiography, *The Education of Henry Adams* (1907), also depicted a stinging description of the education system and modern life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Race was a common issue as well, as seen in the work of Pauline Hopkins, who published five influential works from 1900 to 1903.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Similarly, Sui Sin Far wrote about Chinese-American experiences, and Maria Cristina Mena wrote about Mexican-American experiences.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Prominent among mid-western and western American writers were Willa Cather (1873–1947) and Wallace Stegner (1909–1993), both of whom had a major opus set largely in their regions.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Experimentation in style and form soon joined the new latitudes in subject matter.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1909, Gertrude Stein (1874–1946), by then an expatriate in Paris, published *Three Lives*, an innovative work influenced by her familiarity with cubism, jazz, and other movements in contemporary art and music.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Stein labeled a group of expatriate literary figures who lived in Paris in the 1920s and 1930s the "Lost Generation," a term later used as by Ernest Hemingway.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The 1920s brought sharp changes to American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Many writers had direct experience of World War I, and they used it to frame their writings.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Writers like Henry James, Gertrude Stein, and the poets Ezra Pound, H.D. and T.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Eliot demonstrate the growth of an international perspective in American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Something similar was happening back in the States, as Jewish writers (such as Abraham Cahan) used the English language to reach an international Jewish audience.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The period of peace and debt-fueled economic expansion that followed WWI was the setting for many of the stories and novels of F.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Fitzgerald's work captured the restless, pleasure-hungry, defiant mood of the 1920s, a decade he named the Jazz Age.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Fitzgerald's characteristic theme, expressed poignantly in his masterpiece *The Great Gatsby*, is the tendency of youth's golden dreams to dissolve in failure and disappointment.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Fitzgerald also dwells on the collapse of long-held American Ideals, such as liberty, social unity, good governance and peace, features which were severely threatened by the pressures of modern early 20th century society.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Sinclair Lewis and Sherwood Anderson also wrote novels with critical depictions of American life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] John Dos Passos wrote a famous anti-war novel, *Three Soldiers*, describing scenes of blind hatred, stupidity, and criminality; and the suffocating regimentation of army life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He also wrote about the war in the U.S.A. trilogy which extended into the Depression.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Experimental in form, the U.S.A. trilogy weaves together various narrative strands, which alternate with contemporary news reports, snatches of the author's autobiography, and capsule biographies of public figures including Eugene Debs, Robert La Follette and Isadora Duncan.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Ernest Hemingway (1899-1961), once labelled the "brightest talent of the modern American epoch," was most famous for his production of short stories and novels such as "The Sun Also Rises" and "A Farewell to Arms." In contrast to writers such as F.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Scott Fitzgerald, Hemingway is regarded as the predecessor of literary minimalism, and preferred to write using short prose, avoiding the usage of adverbs and adjectives wherever possible.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Hemingway's adoption of this minimalist style came as a result of his time working as a journalist at the Kansas City Star.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In 1954, Hemingway was awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature, and has persisted as one of the most influential writers, both culturally and stylistically, to have emerged from early 20th-Century America.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Faulkner encompassed a wide range of humanity in Yoknapatawpha County, a Mississippian region of his own invention.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He recorded his characters' seemingly unedited ramblings to represent their inner states, a technique called "stream of consciousness".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He also jumbled time sequences to show how the past – especially the slave-holding era of the Deep South – endures in the present.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among his great works are *Absalom, Absalom!*, *As I Lay Dying*, *The Sound and the Fury*, and *Light in August*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Great Depression-era literature offered blunt, direct social criticism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] John Steinbeck (1902–1968) set many of his stories in Salinas, California, where he was born.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His style was simple and evocative, winning him the favor of the readers but not of the critics.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His poor, working-class characters struggled to lead a decent and honest life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *The Grapes of Wrath* (1939), considered his masterpiece, is a strong, socially-oriented novel of the Joads, a poor family from Oklahoma and their journey to California in search of a better life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other of his popular novels include *Tortilla Flat*, *Of Mice and Men*, *Cannery Row*, and *East of Eden*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He was awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1962.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In his short life, Nathanael West produced two short novels that later came to be considered classics.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *Miss Lonelyhearts* plumbs the life of reluctant (and, to comic effect, male) advice columnist who cannot deal with the tragic letters he receives.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] *The Day of the Locust* satirizes Hollywood stereotypes and the dark ironies of Hollywood life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In non-fiction, James Agee's *Let Us Now Praise Famous Men* observes and depicts the lives of three struggling tenant-farming families in Alabama in 1936.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Combining factual reporting with poetic beauty, Agee presented an accurate and detailed report of what he had seen coupled with insight into his feelings about the experience and the difficulties of capturing it for a broad audience.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In doing so, he created an enduring portrait of a nearly invisible segment of the American population.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Henry Miller's semi-autobiographical novels of sexual exploration, written and published in Paris, were deemed pornographic and officially banned from the United States until 1962.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] By then, the themes and stylistic innovations in *Tropic of Cancer* (1934) and *Black Spring* had already set an example that paved the way for sexually frank novels of personal experience of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The period was dominated by the last few of the realistic modernists, the wildly Romantic beatniks, and explorations of personal, racial, and ethnic themes.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] World War II was the subject of several major novels: Norman Mailer's *The Naked and the Dead* (1948), Joseph Heller's *Catch-22* (1961) and Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s *Slaughterhouse-Five* (1969).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Though born in Canada, Chicago raised Saul Bellow became one of the most influential American writers.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Works like *The Adventures of Augie March* (1953) and *Herzog* (1964), Bellow painted vivid portraits of Jewish life in America that opened the way for further work.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] He was honored by the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1976.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Salinger's *The Catcher in the Rye* (1951), Sylvia Plath's *The Bell Jar* (1963), and Russian-American Vladimir Nabokov's *Lolita* (1955).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The highly popular *To Kill a Mockingbird* (1960) by Harper Lee was a less intense novel of racial inequality and white responsibility.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The 1950s poetry and fiction of the "Beat Generation" developed, initially from a New York circle of intellectuals and then established more officially later in San Francisco.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The term *Beat* referred to the countercultural rhythm of the Jazz scene, to a sense of rebellion regarding the conservative stress of post-war society, and to an interest in new forms of spiritual experience through drugs, alcohol, philosophy, and religion (specifically Zen Buddhism).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Allen Ginsberg set the tone with his Whitmanesque poem *Howl* (1956), a work that begins: "I saw the best minds of my generation destroyed by madness".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among the achievements of the Beats, in the novel, are Jack Kerouac's *On the Road* (1957), the chronicle of a soul-searching travel through the continent, and William S.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Burroughs's *Naked Lunch* (1959), a more experimental work structured as a series of vignettes relating, among other things, the narrator's travels and experiments with hard drugs.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In contrast, John Updike approached American life from a more reflective but no less subversive perspective.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Notable among Updike's characteristic innovations was his use of present-tense narration, his rich, stylized language, and his attention to sensual detail.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His work is also deeply imbued with Christian themes.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The two final installments of the Rabbit series, *Rabbit is Rich* (1981) and *Rabbit at Rest* (1990), were both awarded the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other notable works include the Henry Bech novels (1970–98), *The Witches of Eastwick* (1984), *Roger's Version* (1986) and *In the Beauty of the Lilies* (1996), which literary critic Michiko Kakutani called "arguably his finest".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Frequently linked with Updike is the novelist Philip Roth.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Roth vigorously explores Jewish identity in American society, especially in the postwar era and the early 21st century.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Frequently set in Newark, New Jersey, Roth's work is known to be highly autobiographical, and many of Roth's main characters, most famously the Jewish novelist Nathan Zuckerman, are thought to be alter egos of Roth.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] With these techniques, and armed with his articulate and fast-paced style, Roth explores the distinction between reality and fiction in literature while provocatively examining American culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] His most famous work includes the Zuckerman novels, the controversial *Portnoy's Complaint* (1969), and *Goodbye, Columbus* (1959).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among the most decorated American writers of his generation, he has won every major American literary award, including the Pulitzer Prize for his major novel *American Pastoral* (1997).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the realm of African-American literature, Ralph Ellison's 1952 novel *Invisible Man* was instantly recognized as among the most powerful and important works of the immediate post-war years.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] The story of a black Underground Man in the urban north, the novel laid bare the often repressed racial tension that still prevailed while also succeeding as an existential character study.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Because of its polemical themes and Wright's involvement with the Communist Party, the novel's final part, "American Hunger", was not published until 1977.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Perhaps the most ambitious and challenging post-war American novelist was William Gaddis, whose uncompromising, satiric, and large novels, such as *The Recognitions* (1955) and *J R* (1975) are presented largely in terms of unattributed dialog that requires almost unexampled reader participation.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Gaddis's primary themes include forgery, capitalism, religious zealotry, and the legal system, constituting a sustained polyphonic critique of modern American life.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Gaddis's work, though largely ignored for years, anticipated and influenced the development of such ambitious "postmodern" writers of fiction such as Thomas Pynchon, David Foster Wallace, Joseph McElroy, William H.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Another neglected and challenging postwar American novelist, albeit one who wrote much shorter works, was John Hawkes, whose surreal visionary fiction addresses themes of violence and eroticism and experiments audaciously with narrative voice and style.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among his most important works is the short nightmarish novel *The Lime Twig* (1961).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] In the postwar period, the art of the short story again flourished.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Among its most respected practitioners was Flannery O'Connor, who developed a distinctive Southern gothic esthetic in which characters acted at one level as people and at another as symbols.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Other important practitioners of the form include Katherine Anne Porter, Eudora Welty, John Cheever, Raymond Carver, Tobias Wolff, and the more experimental Donald Barthelme.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p01] Major American essayists of the 20th century included writers such as James Baldwin, Gore Vidal, Susan Sontag, Flannery O'Connor and Joan Didion.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Though its exact parameters remain disputable, from the early 1990s to the present day the most salient literary movement has been postmodernism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In 1973, he published *Gravity's Rainbow*, a leading work in this genre, which won the National Book Award and was unanimously nominated for the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction that year.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Toni Morrison, recipient of the Nobel Prize in Literature, writing in a distinctive lyrical prose style, published her controversial debut novel, *The Bluest Eye*, to critical acclaim in 1970.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Writing in a lyrical, flowing style that eschews excessive use of the comma and semicolon, recalling William Faulkner and Ernest Hemingway in equal measure, Cormac McCarthy seizes on the literary traditions of several regions of the United States and includes multiple genres.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] His novels are noted for achieving both commercial and critical success, several of his works having been adapted to film.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Don DeLillo, who rose to literary prominence with the publication of his 1985 novel, *White Noise*, a work broaching the subjects of death and consumerism and doubling as a piece of comic social criticism, began his writing career in 1971 with *Americana*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] He is listed by Harold Bloom as being among the preeminent contemporary American writers, in the company of such figures as Philip Roth, Cormac McCarthy, and Thomas Pynchon.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] His 1997 novel *Underworld* chronicles American life through and immediately after the Cold War and is usually considered his masterpiece.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] It was also the runner-up in a survey that asked writers to identify the most important work of fiction of the last 25 years.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Among his other important novels are *Libra* (1988), *Mao II* (1991) and *Falling Man* (2007).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Seizing on the distinctly postmodern techniques of digression, narrative fragmentation and elaborate symbolism, and strongly influenced by the works of Thomas Pynchon, David Foster Wallace began his writing career with *The Broom of the System*, published to moderate acclaim in 1987.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In addition to his novels, he also authored three acclaimed short story collections: *Girl with Curious Hair* (1989), *Brief Interviews with Hideous Men* (1999) and *Oblivion: Stories* (2004).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Jonathan Franzen, Wallace's friend and contemporary, rose to prominence after the 2001 publication of his National Book Award-winning third novel, *The Corrections*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] He began his writing career in 1988 with the well-received *The Twenty-Seventh City*, a novel centering on his native St.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Louis, but did not gain national attention until the publication of his essay, "Perchance to Dream", in *Harper's Magazine*, discussing the cultural role of the writer in the new millennium through the prism of his own frustrations.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] *The Corrections*, a tragicomedy about the disintegrating Lambert family, has been called "the literary phenomenon of [its] decade" and was ranked as one of the greatest novels of the past century.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In 2010, he published *Freedom* to great critical acclaim.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Autofiction is a literary movement that has gained steam in American literature throughout the 21st century.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Coined in 1977 by French author Serge Doubrovsky, the autofictional subgenre blends autobiography and fiction, thereby allowing authors to go beyond the limitations of form and substance imposed by these genres.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] A well-established term in the French literary world, it has been less discussed in American literary criticism, despite the recent proliferation of such novels.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Notable American authors known to have written in the autofiction genre include Bret Easton Ellis, Sheila Heti, Maggie Nelson, Chris Kraus, and Ben Lerner.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Puritan poetry was highly religious, and one of the earliest books of poetry published was the *Bay Psalm Book* (1640), a set of translations of the biblical Psalms; however, the translators' intention was not to create literature, but to create hymns that could be used in worship.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] It was published in the same year that anti-Puritan Charles II was restored to the British throne.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] He followed it two years later with *God's Controversy With New England*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Nicholas Noyes was also known for his doggerel verse.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The 18th century saw an increasing emphasis on America itself as fit subject matter for its poets.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] This trend is most evident in the works of Philip Freneau (1752–1832), who is also notable for the unusually sympathetic attitude to Native Americans, which was reflective of his skepticism toward American culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] However, this late colonial-era poetry generally was influenced by contemporary poetry in Europe.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The work of Rebecca Hammond Lard (1772–1855), is still relevant today, writing about the environment as well as also human nature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The Fireside Poets (also known as the Schoolroom or Household Poets) were some of America's first major poets domestically and internationally.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] They included Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, William Cullen Bryant, John Greenleaf Whittier, James Russell Lowell, and Oliver Wendell Holmes Sr.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Longfellow achieved the highest level of acclaim and is often considered the first internationally acclaimed American poet, being the first American poet given a bust in Westminster Abbey's Poets' Corner.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Walt Whitman (1819–1892) and Emily Dickinson (1830–1886), considered two of America's greatest 19th-century poets, could hardly have been more different in temperament and style.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Walt Whitman was a working man, a traveler, a self-appointed nurse during the American Civil War (1861–1865), and a poetic innovator.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] His magnum opus was *Leaves of Grass*, in which he uses a free-flowing verse and lines of irregular length to depict the all-inclusiveness of American democracy.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Taking that motif one step further, the poet equates the vast range of American experience with himself without being egotistical.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] For example, in *Song of Myself*, the long, central poem in *Leaves of Grass*, Whitman writes: "These are really the thoughts of all men in all ages and lands, they are not original with me".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In his words Whitman was a poet of "the body electric".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In *Studies in Classic American Literature*, the English novelist D.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] By contrast, Emily Dickinson lived the sheltered life of a genteel unmarried woman in small-town Amherst, Massachusetts.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Her poetry is ingenious, witty, and penetrating.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Her work was unconventional for its day, and little of it was published during her lifetime.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Many of her poems dwell on the topic of death, often with a mischievous twist.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] One, "Because I could not stop for Death", begins, "He kindly stopped for me".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The opening of another Dickinson poem toys with her position as a woman in a male-dominated society and an unrecognized poet: "I'm nobody!
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] American poetry arguably reached its peak in the early-to-mid-20th century, with such noted writers as Wallace Stevens and his *Harmonium* (1923) and *The Auroras of Autumn* (1950), T.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Eliot and his *The Waste Land* (1922), Robert Frost and his *North of Boston* (1914) and *New Hampshire* (1923), Hart Crane and his *White Buildings* (1926) and the epic cycle, *The Bridge* (1930), Ezra Pound, *The Cantos* (1917–1969).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] William Carlos Williams and his epic poem about his New Jersey hometown, *Paterson*, Marianne Moore, E.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Pound's poetry is complex and sometimes obscure, with references to other art forms and to a vast range of Western and Eastern literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Eliot wrote spare, cerebral poetry, carried by a dense structure of symbols.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In *The Waste Land*, he embodied a jaundiced vision of post–World War I society in fragmented, haunted images.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Like Pound's, Eliot's poetry could be highly allusive, and some editions of *The Waste Land* come with footnotes supplied by the poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In 1948, Eliot won the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Other notable poets of the late 20th century include Louise Glück, Mary Oliver, Gary Snyder, Robert Pinsky, and others.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Stylistic and cultural diversity remain distinguishing features of American poetry.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Notable poets of the 21st century include Amanda Gorman, Saul Williams, Ocean Vuong, Saeed Jones, Alex Dimitrov, Ada Limón, Ben Lerner, and others.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] American dramatic literature, by contrast, remained dependent on European models, although many playwrights did attempt to apply these forms to American topics and themes, such as immigrants, westward expansion, temperance, etc.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] At the same time, American playwrights created several long-lasting American character types, especially the "Yankee", the "Negro" and the "Indian", exemplified by the characters of Jonathan, Sambo and Metamora.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In addition, new dramatic forms were created in the Tom Shows, the showboat theater and the minstrel show.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Realism began to influence American drama, partly through Howells, but also through Europeans such as Henrik Ibsen and Émile Zola.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The most ambitious attempt at bringing modern realism into the drama was James Herne's *Margaret Fleming* (1890), which addressed issues of social determinism through realistic dialogue, psychological insight, and symbolism.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The play was not successful, and both critics and audiences thought it dwelt too much on unseemly topics and included improper scenes, such as the main character nursing her husband's illegitimate child onstage.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In the middle of the 20th century, American drama was dominated by the work of the playwrights Tennessee Williams and Arthur Miller, as well as by the maturation of the American musical, which had found a way to integrate script, music and dance in such works as *Oklahoma!* and *West Side Story*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Later American playwrights of importance include Edward Albee, Sam Shepard, David Mamet, August Wilson and Tony Kushner.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] One of the developments in late-20th-century American literature was the increase of literature written by and about ethnic minorities beyond African Americans and Jewish Americans.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] This development came alongside the growth of the Civil Rights Movement and its corollary, the ethnic pride movement, which led to the creation of Ethnic Studies programs in most major universities.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The second half of the twentieth century saw the emergence of American Jewish writers such as Saul Bellow, Norman Mailer, Joseph Heller, Philip Roth, Chaim Potok, and Bernard Malamud.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Potok's novels about a young New York Jewish boy's coming of age, *The Chosen* and *The Promise* figured prominently in this movement.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] After being relegated to cookbooks and autobiographies for most of the 20th century, Asian American literature achieved widespread notice through Maxine Hong Kingston's fictional memoir, *The Woman Warrior* (1976), and her novels *China Men* (1980) and *Tripmaster Monkey: His Fake Book*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Such poets as Marilyn Chin and Li-Young Lee, Kimiko Hahn and Janice Mirikitani have also achieved prominence, as has playwright David Henry Hwang.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Equally important has been the effort to recover earlier Asian American authors, started by Frank Chin and his colleagues; this effort has brought Sui Sin Far, Toshio Mori, Carlos Bulosan, John Okada, Hisaye Yamamoto and others to prominence.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The Indian-American author Jhumpa Lahiri won the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction for her debut collection of short stories, *Interpreter of Maladies* (1999), and went on to write a well-received novel, *The Namesake* (2003), which was shortly adapted to film in 2007.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] In her second collection of stories, *Unaccustomed Earth*, released to widespread commercial and critical success, Lahiri shifts focus and treats the experiences of the second and third generation.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Hispanic literature also became important during this period, starting with acclaimed novels by Tomás Rivera (*...y no se lo tragó la tierra*) and Rudolfo Anaya (*Bless Me, Ultima*), and the emergence of Chicano theater with Luis Valdez and *Teatro Campesino*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The Dominican-American author Junot Díaz received the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction for his 2007 novel *The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao*, which tells the story of an overweight Dominican boy growing up as a social outcast in Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Another Dominican author, Julia Alvarez, is well known for *How the García Girls Lost Their Accents* and *In the Time of the Butterflies*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The Cuban American author Oscar Hijuelos won a Pulitzer for *The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love*, and Cristina García received acclaim for *Dreaming in Cuban*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Celebrated Puerto Rican novelists who write in English and Spanish include Giannina Braschi, author of the Spanglish classic *Yo-Yo Boing!* and Rosario Ferré, best known for "Eccentric Neighborhoods".
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Puerto Rico has also produced important playwrights such as René Marqués (*The Oxcart*), Luis Rafael Sánchez (*The Passion of Antigone Perez*), and José Rivera (*Marisol*).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Major poets of Puerto Rican diaspora who write about the life of American immigrants include Julia de Burgos (*I was my own route fui*), Giannina Braschi (*Empire of Dreams*), and Pedro Pietri (*Puerto Rican Obituary*).
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Pietri was a co-founder of the Nuyorican Poets Café, a performance space for poetry readings.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] Lin-Manuel Miranda, a Nuyorican poet and playwright, wrote the popular Broadway musicals *Hamilton* and *In the Heights*.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] The success of these authors has brought renewed attention to earlier generations, including Zitkala-Sa, John Joseph Mathews, D'Arcy McNickle and Mourning Dove.
[src:christopher-benfey/american-literature-p02] More recently, Arab American literature, largely unnoticed since the New York Pen League of the 1920s, has become more prominent through the work of Diana Abu-Jaber, whose novels include *Arabian Jazz* and *Crescent* and the memoir *The Language of Baklava*.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Andrew began working at his father's Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, bank, T.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons, in the early 1870s, eventually becoming the leading figure in the institution.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons as Mellon National Bank and established another financial institution, the Union Trust Company in Pittsburgh in 1889.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By the end of 1913, Mellon National Bank held more money in deposits than any other bank in Pittsburgh, and the second-largest bank in the region was controlled by Union Trust.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He was also an influential donor to the Republican Party during the Gilded Age and the Progressive Era.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1921, newly elected president Warren G.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Harding chose Mellon as his secretary of the treasury.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon would remain in office until 1932, serving under Harding, Calvin Coolidge, and Herbert Hoover, all three of whom were members of the Republican Party.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon sought to reform federal taxation in the aftermath of World War I.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He argued cutting tax rates on top earners would generate more tax revenue for the government, but otherwise left in place a progressive income tax.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Some of Mellon's proposals were enacted by the Revenue Act of 1921 and the Revenue Act of 1924, but it was not until the passage of the Revenue Act of 1926 that the "Mellon plan" was fully realized.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He also presided over a reduction in the national debt, which dropped substantially in the 1920s.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's influence in state and national politics reached its zenith during Coolidge's presidency.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's national reputation collapsed following the Wall Street crash of 1929 and the onset of the Great Depression.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He participated in various efforts by the Hoover administration to revive the economy and maintain the international economic order, but opposed direct government intervention in the economy.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After Congress began impeachment proceedings against Mellon, President Hoover shifted Mellon to the position of United States ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon returned to private life after Hoover's defeat in the 1932 presidential election by Franklin D.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Beginning in 1933, the federal government launched a tax fraud investigation on Mellon, leading to a high-profile case that ended with Mellon's estate paying significant sums to settle the matter.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Shortly before his death, in 1937, Mellon helped establish the National Gallery of Art.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] His philanthropic efforts also played a major role in the later establishment of Carnegie Mellon University and the National Portrait Gallery.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's paternal grandparents, both of whom were Ulster Scots, migrated to the United States from County Tyrone, Ireland, in 1818.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With their son, Thomas Mellon, they settled in Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Thomas Mellon established a successful legal practice in Pittsburgh, and in 1843 he married Sarah Jane Negley, an heiress descended from some of the first settlers of Pittsburgh.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Thomas became a wealthy landowner and real estate speculator, and he and his wife had eight children, five of whom survived to adulthood.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Andrew Mellon, the fourth son and sixth child of Thomas and Sarah, was born in 1855.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Thomas Mellon became a prominent member of the local Republican Party, and in 1859 he won election to a position on the Pennsylvania court of common pleas.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Because Thomas was suspicious of both private and public schools, he built a schoolhouse for his children and hired a teacher; Andrew attended this school beginning at age five.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1869, after leaving his judicial position, Thomas Mellon established T.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons, a bank located in Pittsburgh.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Andrew joined his father at the bank, quickly becoming a valued employee despite being in his early teens.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Andrew also attended the Western University of Pennsylvania (which was later renamed the University of Pittsburgh), but he never graduated.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After leaving Western University, Andrew briefly worked at a lumber and coal business before joining T.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons as a full-time employee in 1873.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] That same year, the Panic of 1873 devastated the local and national economy, wiping out a portion of the Mellon fortune.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons, the bank quickly recovered, and by late 1874 the bank's deposits had reached the level they had been at before the onset of the Panic.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons continued to grow after 1873, and in 1876 he was given power of attorney to direct the operations of the bank.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] That same year, Thomas introduced his son to Henry Clay Frick, a customer of the bank who would become one of Mellons's closest friends.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1882, Thomas turned over full ownership of the bank to his son, but Thomas continued to be involved in the bank's activities.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Five years later, Mellon's younger brother, Richard B.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons as a co-owner and vice president.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] During the 1880s, Mellon began to expand the bank's activities.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Along with Frick, Mellon gained control of the Pittsburgh National Bank of Commerce, a national bank that was authorized to print banknotes.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon also acquired or helped found the Union Insurance Company, City Deposit Bank, the Fidelity Title and Trust Company, and the Union Trust Company.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He branched out into industrial concerns, becoming a director of the Pittsburgh Petroleum Exchange and a co-founder of two natural gas companies that collectively controlled 35,000 acres of gas lands in the late 1880s.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1890, Thomas Mellon transferred his properties to Andrew, who would manage the properties on behalf of himself, his parents, and his brothers.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In late 1894, Thomas transferred all of his remaining assets to Andrew.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Despite the large sums entrusted to Andrew, the businesses he ran were still fairly small in the 1890s; T.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons employed seven individuals in 1895.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1889, Mellon agreed to loan $25,000 to the Pittsburgh Reduction Company, a fledgling operation seeking to become the first successful industrial producer of aluminum.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon became a director of the company in 1891, and he and Richard played a major role in the establishment of aluminum factories in New Kensington, Pennsylvania, and Niagara Falls, New York.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The company would emerge as one of the most profitable ventures invested in by the Mellons, and in 1907 it was renamed Alcoa.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Moving into the petroleum industry, the Mellon family also established the Crescent Oil Company, the Crescent Pipeline Company, and the Bear Creek refinery.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By 1894, the Mellon family's vertically integrated companies produced ten percent of the oil exported by the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Partly due to the difficult economic conditions caused by the onset of the Panic of 1893, in 1895 the Mellons sold their oil interests to Standard Oil.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] At roughly the same time they were selling their oil concerns, Andrew and Richard invested in the Carborundum Company, a producer of silicon carbide.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The brothers gained majority ownership of the Carborundum Company in 1898 and replaced the company's founder and president, Edward Goodrich Acheson, with a Carnegie protege, Frank W.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon also invested in mining concerns, becoming vice president of the Trade Dollar Consolidated Mining Company.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon and Henry Clay Frick enjoyed a long-lasting business and social relationship, and Frick frequently hosted Mellon, attorney Philander C.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Knox, inventor George Westinghouse, and others for poker games.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Frick and Mellon both joined the Duquesne Club and, after Frick established the South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club, Mellon became one of that club's first members.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club built the South Fork Dam, which supported an artificial lake that the club used for boating and fishing.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1889, the dam broke, causing the Johnstown Flood, which killed 2,000 people and destroyed 1,600 homes.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the aftermath of the flood, Knox led a legal defense that successfully argued that the club bore no legal responsibility for the flood.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon did not publicly comment on the flood, though he did donate $1,000 to a relief fund.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By the late 1890s, Mellon had amassed a substantial fortune, but his wealth paled in comparison to that of better-known business leaders such as John D.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the late 1890s, the Union Trust Company emerged for the first time as one of Mellon's most important and profitable holdings after Mellon broadened the company's activities to include commercial banking.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With an infusion of capital from Union Trust, Mellon underwrote the capitalization of National Glass and several other companies.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He also became a co-owner of the McClintic-Marshall Construction Company and established Crucible Steel Company, the Pittsburgh Coal Company, and the Monongahela River Coal Company; the two coal companies collectively contributed 11 percent of the coal production of the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With Frick, Richard Mellon, and William Donner, Mellon co-founded Union Steel Company, which specialized in the production of nails and barbed wire.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Though Frick had fallen out with steel magnate and long-time business partner Andrew Carnegie, Mellon received Carnegie's consent to venture into the steel industry.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Responding to the growing emphasis on naval power in the aftermath of the Spanish–American War, Mellon and Frick also became major shareholders in the New York Shipbuilding Corporation.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon & Sons as the Mellon National Bank, a federally chartered National Bank.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Andrew Mellon, Richard Mellon, and Frick drew up a new business arrangement in which the three of them jointly controlled the Union Trust Company, which in turn controlled Mellon National Bank.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] They also established Union Savings Bank, which accepted deposits by mail, and the Mellon banks flourished in the first years of the 20th century.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] While Mellon's financial empire prospered, his investments in other areas, including Pittsburgh's streetcar network, the Union Steel Company (which was bought out by U.S.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Steel), and the Carborundum Company, also paid off handsomely.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Another successful Mellon investment, the Standard Steel Car Company, was created in partnership with three former U.S.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As part of the Texas oil boom, the Mellons also helped J.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The Mellons later removed Guffey as the head of his company, and in 1907 they reorganized the Guffey Company as Gulf Oil and installed William Larimer Mellon Sr.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] (a son of Andrew Mellon's older brother, James Ross Mellon) as the head of Gulf Oil.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The success of Mellon's financial empire and his varied investments made him, according to biographer David Cannadine, the "single most significant individual in the economic life and progress of western Pennsylvania" in the first decade of the 20th century.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The Panic of 1907 devastated several companies based in Pittsburgh, ending a period of strong growth.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Some of Mellon's investments experienced a sustained down period after 1907, but most experienced a quick recovery.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon also became an investor in George Westinghouse's Westinghouse Electric Corporation after he helped prevent the company from going into bankruptcy.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By the end of 1913, Mellon National Bank held more money in deposits than any other bank in Pittsburgh, and the Farmer's Deposit National Bank, which held the second-largest amount of deposits, was controlled by Mellon's Union Trust Company.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1914, Mellon became a co-owner of Koppers, which produced a more sophisticated coking oven than the one that had earlier been pioneered by Frick.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He also served as a director of various other companies, including the Pennsylvania Railroad and the American Locomotive Company.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was deeply involved in the financing of World War I, as the Union Trust Company and other Mellon institutions provided millions of dollars in loans to the United Kingdom and France, and Mellon himself invested in Liberty bonds.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1887, Frick, Andrew, and Richard Mellon jointly purchased Old Overholt, a whiskey distillery located in West Overton, Pennsylvania.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] At the time, Old Overholt was one of the largest and most respected whiskey producers in the country.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1907, as prohibition became more popular across the country, Frick and Mellon removed their names from the distilling license but retained ownership in the company.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] It is believed that Mellon's connections in the Treasury Department are what allowed the company to secure a medicinal permit during Prohibition.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] This permit allowed Overholt to sell existing whiskey stocks to druggists for medicinal use.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] When Frick died in December 1919, he left his share to Mellon.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1925, under pressure from prohibitionists, Mellon sold his share of the company to a New York grocer.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Like his father, Mellon consistently supported the Republican Party, and he frequently donated to state and local party leaders.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Through state party boss Matthew Quay, Mellon influenced legislators to place high tariffs on aluminum products in the McKinley Tariff of 1890.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] During the early 20th century, Mellon was dismayed by the rise of progressivism and the antitrust actions pursued by the presidential administrations of Theodore Roosevelt, William Howard Taft, and Woodrow Wilson.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He especially opposed the Taft administration's investigations into Alcoa, which in 1912 signed a consent decree rather than going to trial.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the aftermath of World War I, he provided financial support to Henry Cabot Lodge and other Republicans in their successful campaign to prevent ratification of the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon attended the 1920 Republican National Convention as a nominal supporter of Pennsylvania Governor William Cameron Sproul (Mellon hoped Senator Philander Knox would win the nomination), but the convention chose Senator Warren G.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Harding of Ohio as the party's presidential nominee.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon strongly approved of the party's conservative platform, and he served as a key fundraiser for Harding during the presidential campaign.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Following Harding's victory in the 1920 presidential election, Harding considered various candidates for Secretary of the Treasury, including Frank Lowden, John W.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Weeks, Charles Dawes, and, at the urging of Senator Knox, Andrew Mellon.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By 1920, Mellon was little-known outside of banking circles, but his potential appointment to the cabinet received strong support from bankers and Pennsylvania Republican leaders like Knox, Senator Boies Penrose, and Governor Sproul.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was reluctant to enter public life due to concerns about privacy and a belief that his ownership of various businesses, including Old Overholt distillery, would be a political liability.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] But Mellon also wanted to retire from active participation in business, and he saw a cabinet position as a prestigious capstone to his career.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon agreed to accept appointment as Secretary of the Treasury in February 1921, and his nomination was quickly confirmed by the United States Senate.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Harding paired the nomination of Mellon with that of Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover, who was distrusted by many of the same Senate Republicans who favored Mellon's candidacy.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Before joining the cabinet, Mellon sold his banking stock to his brother, Richard, but he continued to hold his non-banking stock.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Through Richard and other business associates, Mellon continued to be involved with the major decisions of the Mellon business empire during his time in public service, and he occasionally lobbied congressmen on behalf of his businesses.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] His fortune continued to grow, and at one point in the 1920s he paid more in federal income tax than any other individual save John Rockefeller and Henry Ford.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As Treasury Secretary, Mellon focused on balancing the budget and paying off World War I debts in the midst of the Depression of 1920–21; he was largely unconcerned with international affairs and economic matters such as the unemployment rate.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] To Mellon's chagrin, his department was charged with enforcing Prohibition; he did not believe in teetotaling himself and viewed the law as unenforceable.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Aside from balancing the budget, Mellon's top priority was an overhaul of the federal tax code.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The income tax had become a major part of the federal government's revenue system with the passage of the Revenue Act of 1913, and federal taxation on income had increased during World War I to provide funding for the war effort.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Susan Murnane, major reforms to the federal income tax in the aftermath of World War I were "inevitable", but the exact nature of the tax system in the 1920s was debated by conservatives and progressives within the Republican Party.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Unlike the progressives in his party, Mellon rejected the redistributive nature of the taxation system that had been left in place by the Wilson administration.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Owing in part to the high debts left over from the war, Mellon did not join with some conservatives in the party, who favored the virtual abolition of the income tax in favor of high tariff rates, excise taxes, a national sales tax, or some combination thereof.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon instead advocated the retention of a progressive income tax that would serve as an important, but not primary, source of revenue for the federal government.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] His so-called "scientific taxation" was designed to maximize federal revenue while minimizing the impact on business and industry.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The central tenet of Mellon's tax plan was a reduction of the surtax, a progressive tax that affected only high-income earners.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon argued that such a reduction would minimize tax avoidance and would not affect federal revenue because it would lead to greater economic growth.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He hoped that tax reform would encourage high earners to move their savings from tax-exempt state and municipal bonds to taxable, higher yield industrial stocks.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Though much of the tax plan that he proposed had been developed by former Wilson administration officials Russell Cornell Leffingwell and Seymour Parker Gilbert, the press generally referred to it as the "Mellon Plan".
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The Revenue Act of 1918 had set a top marginal income tax rate of 73% and a corporate tax of approximately 10%.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Due in part to the size of the U.S. public debt, which had grown from $1 billion before the war to $24 billion in 1921, the provisions of the Revenue Act of 1918 remained in place when Harding took office.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1921, the Treasury Department and the House Ways and Means Committee jointly prepared a bill setting the top marginal rate at the level advocated by Mellon, but opposition in the Senate from progressives like Senator Robert M.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] La Follette limited the size of the tax cuts.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In November 1921, Congress passed and Harding signed the Revenue Act of 1921, which raised personal tax exemptions and lowered the top marginal tax rate to 58%.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Because it differed from his original proposals, Mellon was displeased by the bill.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He also strongly disapproved of a "Bonus Bill" passed by Congress that would provide for additional compensation to veterans of World War I, partly because he feared it would interfere with his plans to reduce debt and taxes.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With Mellon's support, Harding vetoed the bill, and Congress failed to override the veto.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As the economy recovered from recession and began to experience the prosperity of the Roaring Twenties, Mellon emerged as one of the most renowned figures in the Harding administration.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] One admiring congressman referred to Mellon as the "greatest Secretary of the Treasury since Alexander Hamilton".
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Harding died after suffering a stroke in August 1923, and he was succeeded by Vice President Calvin Coolidge.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon enjoyed closer relations with President Coolidge than he had with President Harding, and Coolidge and Mellon shared similar views on most major issues, including the necessity for further tax cuts.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Coolidge, Mellon, business organizations, and administration allies conducted a publicity campaign designed to convince wavering congressmen to support Mellon's tax plan.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Their efforts were opposed by the coalition of Democrats and progressive Republicans that exercised effective control over the 68th Congress.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In June 1924, Coolidge signed the Revenue Act of 1924, which contained the income tax rates of Garner's bill and also increased the estate tax.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Coolidge signed the bill but simultaneously called for further tax cuts.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Congress also rejected Mellon's proposed constitutional amendment that would have barred the issuance of tax-exempt securities and, over Coolidge's veto, authorized a bonus to World War I veterans.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon did, however, win one legislative victory, as he convinced Congress to create the Board of Tax Appeals to adjudicate disputes between taxpayers and the government.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon had originally planned to retire after one presidential term but decided to remain in the cabinet in the hope of presiding over the full enactment of his taxation proposals.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the 1924 presidential election, the Republicans campaigned on further tax cuts, while both the Democrats and third-party candidate Robert La Follette denounced Mellon's tax proposals as "a device to relieve multi-millionaires at the expense of other taxpayers".
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Buoyed by the strong economy, and overcoming the scandals of the Harding years, Coolidge won re-election by a decisive margin.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Coolidge saw his victory as a mandate to pursue his favored economic policies, including further tax cuts.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] When Congress reconvened after the 1924 elections, it immediately began working on another bill designed to lower tax rates on the highest earners.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In February 1926, Coolidge signed the Revenue Act of 1926, which reduced the top marginal rate to 25%.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was extremely pleased by the passage of the act, because, unlike the Revenue Act of 1921 and the Revenue Act of 1924, the Revenue Act of 1926 closely reflected Mellon's proposals.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In addition to cutting tax rates on top earners, the act also raised the personal exemption for federal income taxes, abolished the gift tax, reduced the estate tax rate, and repealed a provision that had required the public disclosure of federal income tax returns.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Meanwhile, the booming economy fostered a $400 million budget surplus in 1926, and the country's national debt dropped from $24 billion in early 1921 to $19.6 billion at the end of fiscal year 1926.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Government revenues increased considerably under Mellon's plan, largely collected from higher-income earners.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With his top priority of tax reform accomplished, Mellon increasingly turned over management of the Treasury Department to his deputy, Ogden L.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After the 1926 elections, Mellon and Mills sought to cut the corporate tax and fully repeal the estate tax.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The Revenue Act of 1928 did indeed cut the corporate tax, but the estate tax was left unchanged.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon also focused on the construction of new federal buildings, and his efforts led to the construction of several buildings in the Federal Triangle.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Responsibility for foreign relations lay with the State Department rather than the Treasury Department, and Benjamin Strong Jr. and other central bankers took the lead with regard to international monetary policy, but Mellon nonetheless exercised some influence in foreign affairs.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He strongly opposed the cancellation of European debts from World War I but recognized that Britain and other countries would be unable to pay those debts without a renegotiation of terms.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1923, Mellon and British Chancellor of the Exchequer Stanley Baldwin negotiated an agreement in which Britain promised to pay off the debts over a 62-year period.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After the adoption of the Dawes Plan, Mellon reached debt settlements with several other European countries.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After protracted negotiations, the United States and France agreed to the Mellon-Berenger Agreement, which reduced France's debt and set terms for repayment.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Coolidge surprised many observers by announcing that he would not seek another term in August 1927.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The decision left Hoover as the presumed front-runner for the 1928 presidential election, but many conservatives within the party opposed Hoover's candidacy.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The conservative resistance to Hoover centered around Mellon, who controlled Pennsylvania's delegation at the 1928 Republican National Convention and was influential with Republicans throughout the country.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Though they had maintained an amicable relationship in public, Mellon privately distrusted Hoover, resented Hoover's engagement in the affairs of other cabinet departments and feared that a President Hoover would move away from Mellon's tax policies.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Several Republicans urged Mellon to run for president, but Mellon believed that he was too old to seek the presidency.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon attempted to convince Coolidge or Charles Evans Hughes to run, but neither heeded his appeals.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the months before the 1928 Republican Convention, Mellon maintained his neutrality in the presidential race, but with no compelling alternative Republican candidate willing to run, Mellon finally threw his support behind Hoover.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With Mellon's backing, Hoover won the Republican nomination on the first ballot of the convention, and he went on to defeat Al Smith in the 1928 presidential election.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Defying widespread expectations that he would retire, Mellon chose to stay on as Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Along with Secretary of Agriculture James Wilson and Secretary of Labor James J.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Davis, Mellon is one of only three cabinet members to serve in the same post under three consecutive presidents.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Secretary Mellon had helped persuade the Federal Reserve Board to lower interest rates in 1921 and 1924; lower interest rates contributed to a booming economy, but they also encouraged stock market speculation.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1928, responding to increasing fears of the dangers of speculation and a booming stock market, the Federal Reserve Board began raising interest rates.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon favored another interest rate increase in 1929, and in August 1929 the Federal Reserve Board raised the discount rate to six percent.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The higher rate failed to curb speculation, and the activity on the stock market continued to grow.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In October 1929, the New York Stock Exchange suffered the worst crash in its history in what was called "Black Tuesday".
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As the vast majority of Americans did not own shares in the stock market, the crash did not immediately have disastrous effects on the U.S. economy as a whole.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon had little sympathy for the speculators who lost their money, and he was philosophically opposed to an interventionist economic policy designed to address the stock market crash.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nonetheless, Mellon immediately began calling for cuts to the discount rate, which would reach two percent in mid-1930, and successfully urged Congress to pass a bill providing for temporary, across-the-board tax cuts.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon supported the idea of asset liquidation to balance budgets, even if it meant shutting down entire industries.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By mid-1930, many, including Mellon, believed that the economy had already experienced the worst effects of the stock market crash.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He did not object to the Smoot–Hawley Tariff Act, which raised tariff rates to one of the highest levels in U.S. history.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Despite the optimism of Hoover and Mellon, in late 1930 the economy went into a deep slump, as gross national product declined dramatically, and numerous workers lost their jobs.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] While numerous banks failed, Democrats won control of Congress in the 1930 mid-term elections.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As the economy declined, so did Mellon's popularity, which was further damaged by his opposition to another bonus bill for veterans.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In mid-1931, the country entered a deep depression, and, at Hoover's request, Mellon negotiated a moratorium on German debt repayments.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After Mellon returned to the United States in August 1931, he was confronted by another series of bank failures.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Among the banks that failed was the Bank of Pittsburgh, the lone remaining major Pittsburgh bank not controlled by the Mellon family.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Again, following Hoover's lead, Mellon presided over the creation of the National Credit Association, a voluntary initiative among the larger banks that was designed to assist failing institutions.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] As the National Credit Association proved to be ineffective at stemming the tide of bank failures, Congress and the Hoover administration established the Reconstruction Finance Corporation to provide federal loans to banks.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] With the unemployment rate approaching twenty percent, Mellon became one of the most "loathed leaders" in the United States, second only to Hoover himself.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Facing this unprecedented economic catastrophe, Mellon urged Hoover to refrain from using the government to intervene in the depression.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon believed that economic recessions, such as those that had occurred in 1873 and 1907, were a necessary part of the business cycle because they purged the economy.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In his memoirs, Hoover wrote that Mellon advised him to "liquidate labor, liquidate stocks, liquidate the farmers, liquidate real estate.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Facing a large deficit, Mellon and Mills called for a return to the tax rates set by the Revenue Act of 1924 and also sought new taxes on automobiles, gasoline, and other items.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Congress responded by passing the Revenue Act of 1932, which included many of the Treasury Department's proposals.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In early 1932, Congressman Wright Patman of Texas initiated impeachment proceedings against Mellon, contending that Mellon had violated numerous federal laws designed to prevent conflicts of interest.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Though Mellon had defeated similar investigations in the past, his falling popularity left him unable to effectively counter Patman's charges.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Hoover removed Mellon from Washington by offering him the position of ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon accepted the post, and Mills replaced his former boss as Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon arrived in Britain in April 1932, receiving a friendly reception from a country he had often visited over the previous thirty years.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] From his post, he watched the collapse of the international economic order, including the debt accords that he had helped negotiate.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He also convinced the British to allow Gulf Oil to operate in Kuwait, a British protectorate in the oil-rich region of the Persian Gulf.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Defying Mellon's expectations, Hoover was defeated by Franklin D.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Roosevelt in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon left office when Hoover's term ended in March 1933, returning to private life after twelve years of government service.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Knox and Penrose both died in 1921, leaving a power vacuum in Pennsylvania Republican politics.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Along with his nephew, William Larimer Mellon, Mellon became an influential player in Pennsylvania politics, and their support helped ensure the elections of Senator David A.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was unable to assert the same level of control that Boies Penrose had had over state politics, and his leadership of the state party was challenged by William Scott Vare of Philadelphia and progressive leader Gifford Pinchot, who won the 1922 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nonetheless, Mellon would continue to exert an important influence on Pennsylvania politics throughout the 1920s, especially in senatorial elections and in Allegheny County.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's influence over state politics waned in the early 1930s, as the progressive allies of Governor Pinchot took control of the state Republican Party.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Numerous financial institutions failed in the months prior to Roosevelt's inauguration, but Mellon National Bank, the Union Trust Company, and another Mellon banking operation, Mellbank Corporation, were all able to avoid closure.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon strongly opposed Roosevelt's New Deal policies, especially the 1933 Banking Act, which required separation between commercial and investment banking.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon believed that the various New Deal policies, including Social Security and unemployment insurance, undermined the free market system that had produced one of the largest economies in the world.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Aside from banking reform, other New Deal policies, including regulations on utilities and coal mines and laws designed to promote labor unions, also affected Mellon's business empire.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Additionally, the Revenue Act of 1934 and the Revenue Act of 1935 rescinded many of Mellon's tax policies and contained other provisions that were designed to increase taxation on top earners and corporations.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Even after leaving office, Mellon continued to be vilified by many in the public, and in 1933 Harvey O'Connor published a popular and unfavorable biography, *Mellon's Millions*.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Democrats won effective control of Allegheny County in the 1933 elections, and the following year Democrat Joseph F.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Guffey won Pennsylvania's Senate election and George Howard Earle III won the state's gubernatorial election.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon endured numerous attacks during these campaigns, and his unpopularity in Pittsburgh led him to spend most of his final years in Washington rather than his home town.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the 1930s, the Roosevelt administration conducted several high-profile tax evasion prosecutions against individuals such as Thomas W.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In response to accusations levied by Republican Congressman Louis Thomas McFadden of Pennsylvania in early 1933, Attorney General Homer Cummings began an inquiry into Mellon's tax history.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Between February 1935 and May 1936, the Board of Tax Appeals heard a widely covered case in which the federal government accused Mellon of tax fraud.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] During the proceedings, Mellon divulged numerous details of his business career that had previously been unknown to the public.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was diagnosed with cancer in November 1936.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] His health declined in 1937, and he died on August 26, 1937.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Newspapers across the country took note of his death.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the early 1880s, Mellon had a serious relationship with Fannie Larimer Jones, but he broke off the relationship after learning that she was suffering from tuberculosis.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After this experience, Mellon refrained from courting women for several years.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1898, while traveling with Frick and Frick's wife to Europe, Mellon met Nora McMullen, a nineteen-year-old Englishwoman of Ulster Scots ancestry.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon visited McMullen's home of Hertford Castle in 1898 and 1899, and, after a period of courtship, the couple married in 1900.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nora gave birth to a daughter, Ailsa, in 1901.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nora disliked living in Pittsburgh, and she was unhappy in her marriage.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] By the end of 1903, she had begun an affair with Alfred George Curphey, who would also later be involved with the wife of George Vivian, 4th Baron Vivian.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon and Nora eventually reconciled, and in 1907 she gave birth to a son, Paul.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The reconciliation proved short-lived, as Nora took up with Curphey again in 1908 and requested a divorce the following year.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] To avoid a public scandal, Andrew reluctantly agreed to a separation in 1909.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Seeking to hold divorce proceedings privately before a judge rather than publicly before a jury, in 1911 Mellon convinced the Pennsylvania legislature to amend a law that had required a jury trial in divorce proceedings.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In response, Nora attacked Mellon in the press, and the divorce proceedings were widely covered by the media.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nora went so far to contest the divorce that she made an appeal to King George of England and parliament.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1912, Mellon and Nora finally agreed on a divorce settlement, largely on Mellon's terms.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Nora lived in Pittsburgh for several years before eventually settling in the Hudson Valley, and the two children alternated living with either parent.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1923, Nora married Harvey Arthur Lee, a British-born antiques dealer 14 years her junior.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Two years after the Lees' divorce in 1928, Nora Lee resumed the surname Mellon, at the request of her son, Paul.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the 1920s, while Mellon served as Secretary of the Treasury, Ailsa was courted by several influential men, including Otto Christian Archibald von Bismarck, Robert Horne, and Gelasio Caetani.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1926, in the "greatest society event that the nation's capital had witnessed" since before World War I, Ailsa married David K.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Bruce, son of Democratic Senator William Cabell Bruce of Maryland.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] After attending Yale University and the University of Cambridge, Paul briefly worked at Mellon National Bank.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He later settled in Virginia, becoming a well-known philanthropist.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's nephew, Richard King Mellon, succeeded Andrew as the head of the Mellon financial empire.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Emulating his father, Mellon eschewed philanthropy for much of his life, but in the early 1900s, he began donating to local organizations such as the YMCA.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon committed to his first large-scale act of philanthropy in 1913, when he and his brother, Richard, established the Mellon Institute of Industrial Research as a department of the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1967, the institute merged with the Carnegie Institute of Technology to form Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon also served as an alumni president and trustee of the University of Pittsburgh, and made several major donations to the school, including the land on which the Cathedral of Learning and Heinz Chapel were constructed.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In total it is estimated that Mellon donated over $43 million to the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Encouraged by Frick and guided by Charles Carstairs, Mellon began collecting art in the mid-to-late 1890s.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Over the ensuing decades, his art collection continued to grow as he purchased pieces from Knoedler and Joseph Duveen, and during the 1920s his collection was generally considered to be one of the finest art collections in Washington.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the early 1930s, he purchased twenty-one paintings from the Soviet Union's Hermitage Museum in the Soviet sale of Hermitage paintings.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Some of these were among the best paintings held by the Hermitage.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] They were all subsequently given to the National Gallery of Art.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon decided to use his fortune and art collection to establish a national art museum in Washington modeled after the National Gallery in London.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In 1936, Mellon presented President Roosevelt with an offer to establish a national art museum to which Mellon would donate his art collection as well as an endowment, while the federal government would pay for the institution's upkeep.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] He conditioned the offer on the establishment of a board of trustees, a majority of whom would be chosen by Mellon.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Despite the ongoing tax case against Mellon, the Roosevelt administration accepted the offer, and Congress passed legislation authorizing the construction of the National Gallery of Art on Mellon's terms.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The National Gallery of Art (now known as the West Building) opened in 1941.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Two of his children, Paul Mellon and Ailsa Mellon Bruce, were subsequently among the major donors to the collection.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] The Mellon Foundation and several family members funded a new museum building, called the East Building, which opened in 1978.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon's friend and former employee, David E.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Finley Jr., would later preside over the establishment of the National Portrait Gallery, which also hosts several paintings donated by Mellon.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon was initiated to the Scottish Rite Freemasonry, till he raised the 33rd and highest degree.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon Memorial Fountain in Washington was created by Sidney Waugh and was dedicated in May 1952 by Harry S.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Washington, D.C., also hosts the Andrew W.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon Auditorium and the Andrew Mellon Building.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon Foundation, the product of the merger of the Avalon Foundation and the Old Dominion Foundation (set up separately by his children), is named in his honor, as is the 378-foot US Coast Guard Cutter *Mellon (WHEC-717)*.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon appears in the HBO drama series *Boardwalk Empire*, in the fifth, eighth and twelfth episodes of the third season, in his capacity as Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] His character is played by Carnegie Mellon alumnus James Cromwell.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] In the alternate history/time travel story "A Slip in Time" by S.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Stirling, featuring a history in which the First World War was avoided and the Austro-Hungarian Empire survived, Andrew Mellon was the President of the United States in 1926.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Mellon is the subject of three unflattering chapters in Matt Stoller's 2019 book, *Goliath: The 100 Year War Between Monopoly Power and Democracy*, which recounts efforts by populists in Washington (namely, Congressman Wright Patman; Roosevelt administration lawyer Robert H.
[src:christopher-benfey/andrew-w-mellon] Jackson; and Ferdinand Pecora, attorney for the Senate Banking Committee) to expose Mellon's crimes and abuse of power for personal gain.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Richards, Dorothea Rockburne, Michael Rumaker, Ben Shahn, Aaron Siskind, Cy Twombly, Knute Stiles, Frank Weise, and Stefan Wolpe.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The school closed in 1957 due to funding issues; Camp Rockmont for Boys now sits on the campus' site.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The history and legacy of Black Mountain College are preserved and extended by the Black Mountain College Museum + Arts Center in nearby Asheville, North Carolina.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The institution was established to "avoid the pitfalls of autocratic chancellors and trustees and allow for a more flexible curriculum," and "with the holistic aim 'to educate a student as a person and a citizen," according to historian Eva Díaz.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Black Mountain was experimental in nature and committed to an interdisciplinary approach, prioritizing art-making as a necessary component of education and attracting a faculty and lecturers that included many of America's leading visual artists, composers, poets, and designers.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] During the 1930s and 1940s the school flourished, becoming well known as an incubator for artistic talent.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Notable events at the school were common; it was here that the first large-scale geodesic dome was made by faculty member Buckminster Fuller and students, where Merce Cunningham formed his dance company, and where John Cage staged his first musical happening.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In the 1950s, the focus of the school shifted to the literary arts under the rectorship of Charles Olson.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Olson founded *The Black Mountain Review* in 1954 and, together with his colleague and student Robert Creeley, developed the poetic school of Black Mountain poets.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In 1952, a seminal pottery workshop took place that commingled Eastern and Western traditions and sensibilities, influencing many mid-20th century studio potters.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The College was an important incubator for the American avant-garde.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Bennington College in Bennington, Vermont, based on the same philosophy, was founded one year before Black Mountain College.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The school operated using non-hierarchical methodologies that placed students and educators on the same plane.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Revolving around 20th-century ideals about the value and importance of balancing education, art, and cooperative labor, students were required to participate in farm work, construction projects, and kitchen duty as part of their holistic education.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The students were involved at all levels of institutional decision-making.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] They were also left in charge of deciding when they were ready to graduate, which notoriously few ever did.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] There were no course requirements, official grades (except for transfer purposes), or accredited degrees.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Graduates were presented with handcrafted diplomas as purely ceremonial symbols of their achievement.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The liberal arts program offered at Black Mountain was broad, and supplemented by art making as a means of cultivating creative thinking within all fields.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] While Josef Albers led the school, the only two requirements were a course on materials and form taught by Albers and a course on Plato.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In 1933, the Nazi Party shut down the Bauhaus in Germany, a similarly progressive arts-based educational institution.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Many of the school's faculty left Europe for the US, and a number of them settled at Black Mountain, most notably Josef Albers, who was selected to run the art program, and his wife Anni Albers, who taught weaving and textile design.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Adolf Hitler's rise to power and the subsequent persecution taking place in Europe led many artists and intellectuals to flee and resettle in the US, populating Black Mountain College with an influx of both students and faculty.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In addition, the college was operating in the South during the period of legal racial segregation at other colleges and universities in the region.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] While not immune from racial tensions, the student Alma Stone Williams, an African-American woman who enrolled at Black Mountain College in 1944, is considered by some to be the first black student to enroll in an all-white institution of higher education in the South during the Jim Crow era.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Notable African-American instructors included Carol Brice and Roland Hayes during the 1945 Summer Music Institute; Percy H.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Baker, hired on full-time in 1945; Jacob Lawrence and Gwendolyn Knight during the 1946 Summer Art Institute; and Mark Oakland Fax for the Spring 1946 quarter.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The Julius Rosenwald Fund provided African-American teachers' salaries as well as student scholarships.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The college originally rented the YMCA Blue Ridge Assembly buildings south of Black Mountain, North Carolina, founded and owned by another progressive educator, Willis D.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In 1937, it purchased a 667-acre (270 ha) property across the valley at Lake Eden.:8 This property, developed by E.W.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Grove (of the Grove Park Inn and Grove Arcade in Asheville) as a summer resort for residents of his nearby Grovemont neighborhood, included a gate house, dining hall, sleeping lodges, several cottages and other structures.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The property was later purchased and converted to an ecumenical Christian boys' residential summer camp (Camp Rockmont).
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] This has been used for years as the site of the Black Mountain Festival, the Lake Eden Arts Festival (LEAF), and Black Mountain College Museum + Arts Center's {Re}HAPPENING.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] A number of the original structures are still in use as lodgings or administrative facilities, and two frescoes painted by Jean Charlot remain intact on the site.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Black Mountain College closed in 1957, eight years after Albers left to direct the first design department at Yale University.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The college suspended classes by court order due to debts; the school was unable to sustain itself financially given the greatly decreased number of students.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] In 1962, the school's books were finally closed, with all debts covered.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The Black Mountain College Museum + Arts Center, founded in 1993 in Asheville, continues the legacy of Black Mountain College through talks, exhibitions, performances, collection and preservation, and an annual fall conference that examines the college's history and impact.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The Journal of Black Mountain College Studies is a multidisciplinary open-access digital publication that publishes articles, essays, and creative work related to the school and the individuals associated with it.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Black Mountain College was the subject of the museum exhibition *Leap Before You Look: Black Mountain College 1933–1957,* which opened at the Institute of Contemporary Art, Boston on October 10, 2015.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The show was curated by Helen Molesworth with Ruth Erickson.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The show later exhibited at the Hammer Museum from February 21 to May 15, 2016.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] The accompanying catalog included contributions from curators and scholars such as Brenda Danilowitz, Eva Díaz, Nancy Perloff, Alice Sebrell, Jenni Sorkin, and Gloria Sutton, among others.
[src:christopher-benfey/black-mountain-college] Black Mountain College was featured in Nicholas Sparks' novel, *The Longest Ride* (2013) and the 2015 movie adaptation of the same name.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] Benfey was born in Merion, Pennsylvania, but spent most of his childhood in Richmond, Indiana. and attended The Putney School.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] His father was a German immigrant and his mother was from North Carolina.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] He began his undergraduate studies at Earlham College, where his father, Otto Theodor Benfey, was a professor in the Chemistry department, and completed his B.A. at Guilford College.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] Benfey holds a Ph.D. in Comparative Literature from Harvard University.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] Benfey is a specialist in 19th and 20th century American literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] He is also an established essayist and critic who has been published in *The Atlantic*, *The New York Times Sunday Book Review*, *The New Republic*, *The New York Review of Books*, and *The Times Literary Supplement*.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] Mellon Professor of English at Mount Holyoke College, where he has taught since 1989.
[src:christopher-benfey/christopher-benfey] He is a Guggenheim Fellow, as well as a fellow of the National Endowment for the Humanities.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The characteristically intercultural and transnational field of comparative literature concerns itself with the relation between literature, broadly defined, and other spheres of human activity, including history, politics, philosophy, art, and science.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Students and instructors in the field, usually called "comparatists", have traditionally been proficient in several languages and acquainted with the literary traditions, literary criticism, and major literary texts of those languages.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Many of the newer sub-fields, however, are more influenced by critical theory and literary theory, stressing theoretical acumen and the ability to consider different types of art concurrently over proficiency in multiple languages.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The interdisciplinary nature of the field means that comparatists typically exhibit acquaintance with sociology, history, anthropology, translation studies, critical theory, cultural studies, and religious studies.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] As a result, comparative literature programs within universities may be designed by scholars drawn from several such departments.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] This eclecticism has led critics (from within and without) to charge that comparative literature is insufficiently well-defined, or that comparatists too easily fall into dilettantism because the scope of their work is, by definition, broad.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The terms "comparative literature" and "world literature" are often used to designate a similar course of study and scholarship.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Comparative literature is the more widely used term in the United States, with many universities having comparative literature departments or comparative literature programs.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Defined most broadly, comparative literature is the study of "literature without borders".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] What scholars in comparative literature share is a desire to study literature beyond national boundaries and an interest in languages so that they can read foreign texts in their original form.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Many comparatists also share the desire to integrate literary experience with other cultural phenomena such as historical change, philosophical concepts, and social movements.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The discipline of comparative literature has scholarly associations such as the International Comparative Literature Association (ICLA) and comparative literature associations in many countries.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] There are many learned journals that publish scholarship in comparative literature: see "Selected Comparative Literature and Comparative Humanities Journals".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] For a list of books in comparative literature, see "Bibliography of (Text)Books in Comparative Literature".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Work considered foundational to the discipline of comparative literature include Spanish humanist Juan Andrés's work, Transylvanian Hungarian Hugo Meltzl de Lomnitz's scholarship, also the founding editor of the journal *Acta Comparationis Litterarum Universarum* (1877) and Irish scholar H.M.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Posnett's *Comparative Literature* (1886).
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] However, antecedents can be found in the ideas of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe in his vision of "world literature" (*Weltliteratur)* and Russian Formalists credited Alexander Veselovsky with laying the groundwork for the discipline.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Viktor Zhirmunsky, for instance, referred to Veselovsky as "the most remarkable representative of comparative literary study in Russian and European scholarship of the nineteenth century".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] During the late 19th century, comparatists such as Fyodor Buslaev were chiefly concerned with deducing the purported Zeitgeist or "spirit of the times", which they assumed to be embodied in the literary output of each nation.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Thus a scholar might attempt to trace how a particular literary idea or motif traveled between nations over time.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] In the French School of Comparative Literature, the study of influences and mentalities dominates.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Today, the French School practices the nation-state approach of the discipline although it also promotes the approach of a "European Comparative Literature".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The publications from this school include, *La Littérature Comparée* (1967) by C.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Rousseau, *La Critique Littéraire* (1969) by J.-C.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Carloni and Jean Filloux and *La Littérature Comparée* (1989) by Yves Cheverel, translated into English as *Comparative Literature Today: Methods & Perspectives* (1995).
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Like the French School, German Comparative Literature has its origins in the late 19th century.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] After World War II, the discipline developed to a large extent owing to one scholar in particular, Peter Szondi (1929–1971), a Hungarian who taught at the Free University Berlin.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Szondi welcomed, among others, Jacques Derrida (before he attained worldwide recognition), Pierre Bourdieu and Lucien Goldman from France, Paul de Man from Zürich, Gershom Sholem from Jerusalem, Theodor W.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Adorno from Frankfurt, Hans Robert Jauss from the then young University of Konstanz, and from the US René Wellek, Geoffrey Hartman and Peter Demetz (all at Yale), along with the liberal publicist Lionel Trilling.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The names of these visiting scholars, who form a programmatic network and a methodological canon, epitomize Szondi's conception of comparative literature.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] However, German comparatists working in East Germany were not invited, nor were recognized colleagues from France or the Netherlands.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] These concepts continue to have profound implications for comparative literary theory today" ...
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] A manual published by the department of comparative literature at the LMU Munich lists 31 German departments which offer a diploma in comparative literature in Germany, albeit some only as a 'minor'.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] This situation is undergoing rapid change, however, since many universities are adapting to the new requirements of the recently introduced Bachelor and Master of Arts.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] German comparative literature is being squeezed by the traditional philologies on the one hand and more vocational programmes of study on the other which seek to offer students the practical knowledge they need for the working world (e.g., 'Applied Literature').
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] With German universities no longer educating their students primarily for an academic market, the necessity of a more vocational approach is becoming ever more evident".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Reacting to the French School, postwar scholars, collectively termed the "American School", sought to return the field to matters more directly concerned with literary criticism, de-emphasising the detective work and detailed historical research that the French School had demanded.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] One monument to the approach of this period is Erich Auerbach's book *Mimesis: The Representation of Reality in Western Literature*, a survey of techniques of realism in texts whose origins span several continents and three thousand years.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The approach of the American School would be familiar to current practitioners of cultural studies and is even claimed by some to be the forerunner of the Cultural Studies boom in universities during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] The field today is highly diverse: for example, comparatists routinely study Chinese literature, Arabic literature and the literatures of most other major world languages and regions as well as English and continental European literatures.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] There is a movement among comparativists in the United States and elsewhere to re-focus the discipline away from the nation-based approach with which it has previously been associated towards a cross-cultural approach that pays no heed to national borders.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] It remains to be seen whether this approach will prove successful given that comparative literature had its roots in nation-based thinking and much of the literature under study still concerns issues of the nation-state.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Given developments in the studies of globalization and interculturalism, comparative literature, already representing a wider study than the single-language nation-state approach, may be well suited to move away from the paradigm of the nation-state.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Joseph Hankinson's stress on comparison's 'affiliative' potential is one recent effort in this direction.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] While in the West comparative literature is experiencing institutional constriction, there are signs that in many parts of the world the discipline is thriving, especially in Asia, Latin America, the Caribbean, and the Mediterranean.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Current trends in Transnational studies also reflect the growing importance of post-colonial literary figures such as J.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Coetzee, Maryse Condé, Earl Lovelace, V.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Naipaul, Michael Ondaatje, Wole Soyinka, Derek Walcott, and Lasana M.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] For recent post-colonial studies in North America see George Elliott Clarke.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] *Directions Home: Approaches to African-Canadian Literature*.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] (University of Toronto Press, 2011), Joseph Pivato.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] (Guernica Editions, 2003), and "The Sherbrooke School of Comparative Canadian Literature".
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] In the area of comparative studies of literature and the other arts see Linda Hutcheon's work on opera and her *A Theory of Adaptation*.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Canadian scholar Joseph Pivato is carrying on a campaign to revitalize comparative study with his book, *Comparative Literature for the New Century* eds.
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] Giulia De Gasperi & Joseph Pivato (2018).
[src:christopher-benfey/comparative-literature] In response to Pivato Canadian comparatists Susan Ingram and Irene Sywenky co-edited *Comparative Literature in Canada: Contemporary Scholarship, Pedagogy, and Publishing in Review* (2019), an initiative of the Canadian Comparative Literature Association.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham was founded in 1847 as the **Friends Boarding School**, a boarding high school for the religious education of Quaker adolescents.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In 1859, Earlham became **Earlham College**, upon the addition of collegiate academics.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] At this time, Earlham was the third Quaker college in the United States (Haverford College was first, Guilford College the second), and the second U.S. institution of higher education to be coeducational (Oberlin College was first).
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Though the college initially admitted only students who belonged to the Religious Society of Friends, Earlham began admitting non-Quakers in 1865.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The college was named for Earlham Hall, home of the Gurneys, an important English Quaker family.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Over time, as Quakerism in America became more progressive, Earlham's practices changed with them.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The college has still remained faithful to its Quaker roots.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] 1960 marked the establishment of the Earlham School of Religion, then the only Friends seminary in the world.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Price as its first African-American president.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Price left the position in July 2018, and in November of that year was appointed director of the John F.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum in Boston.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham's 800-acre (3.2 km2) campus lies at the southwestern edge of Richmond, Indiana, a city of 35,720 (2020 census).
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The main quadrangle of the campus is called "the Heart".
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] It is bordered by Earlham Hall (with the Runyan Center student union directly behind it), Olvey-Andis Hall, Lilly Library, Carpenter Hall, Landrum Bolling Center, the science buildings (Stanley Hall, Noyes Hall and Dennis Hall), Tyler Hall, Bundy Hall and Barrett Hall.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Ninety-four percent of Earlham students live on campus in a variety of settings.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The campus has eight residence halls (Barrett Hall, Bundy Hall, Earlham Hall, Mills Hall, Hoerner Hall, Olvey-Andis Hall, Warren Hall and Wilson Hall).
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In addition, it has 15 theme and friendship houses, which border the North and East edges of the campus.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The school has embarked on major campus improvement projects which cost a combined $62.3 million.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The science complex (Stanley and Noyes Halls) has undergone a complete renovation.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Stanley Hall was completed by fall 2013 and received a LEED Silver certification.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] A new Center for Science and Technology, completed in 2015, obtained a LEED gold rating.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] While Earlham is predominately an undergraduate institution, it also offers a Master of Arts in Teaching degree.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In keeping with Friends' belief in equality, everyone addresses each other at Earlham by his or her first name, without the use of titles such as "doctor" or "professor".
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Roughly 70% of Earlham students go on a semester-length off-campus program to such destinations as Mexico, the U.S./ Mexican border, Vienna, Martinique, Northern Ireland, Great Britain, France, Germany, Spain, New Zealand, Japan, and Tanzania.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In the sciences, Earlham places a large emphasis on integrating research into the undergraduate curriculum.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Through Ford/Knight grants, most science faculty have been or are currently involved with students in research.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham has good representation in the Butler Undergraduate Research Conference, held each year in the spring.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham's biology and chemistry departments have a long history of producing distinguished graduates, such as Warder Clyde Allee, Jim Fowler, Larry E.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Overman, Harold Urey, and Wendell Stanley, the latter two of which won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry (in 1934 and 1946, respectively).
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Students and faculty in Earlham's CS applied groups jointly provide computer infrastructure support for the college.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The choir department organizes regional and national tours every year for its ensembles.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In January 2012, the concert choir performed in Indianapolis, the Cathedral Basilica of St.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The choral and instrumental music departments collaborate on a biennial basis, performing works such as Carmina Burana and Michael Tippett's A Child of Our Time.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The college has a full gamelan ensemble, which performs concerts in the Spring.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham has an entirely student-managed public radio station, WECI 91.5FM.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In addition, 6-10 theater performances occur throughout the year on campus through either the academic department, senior projects or the student company.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham has students from 77 countries, which equates to roughly 200 students.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] This high diversity is due in part to a strong relationship with the United World College network of international boarding high schools.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Since 2004, Earlham College has been a part of the Davis United World Scholars program, which offers need-based scholarships for UWC graduates to continue their education at select institutions in the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The Davis Cup, which is awarded to the college with the most current students from this program, has been awarded to Earlham several times.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The college also draws from all regions of the United States, with students from 42 states.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Domestic minorities represent 15% of the student body.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham is orienting some of the curriculum around exploring local and global problems as well as possible solutions.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In 2016, Earlham students won the million dollar Hult Prize for their "Magic Bus" proposal to help with transportation problems in developing urban environments.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham has the United States' only equestrian program which is run entirely by students.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Lessons are available for students of the college and community members.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The equestrian center is adjacent to the college-owned 11-acre Miller farm which hosts agricultural interns during the school year and summer and "work days" on Saturdays for the rest of the community during the school year.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Miller farm also serves as a residence for upper class students.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In keeping with Quaker tradition, Earlham students voluntarily invest many hours of community service into the Richmond community.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham teams (nicknamed *Quakers*) compete in NCAA Division III and in the Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The women's sports are basketball, cross country, field hockey, golf, indoor track, lacrosse, outdoor track, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The men's sports are baseball, basketball, cross country, golf, indoor track, lacrosse, outdoor track, soccer, and tennis.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] The football team was organized in 1888 and has been playing games since the 1889 season.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] As one of the earliest college programs, Earlham has competed against larger foes such as Indiana University, Purdue University, the University of Kentucky, Ball State University, and Butler University.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Perhaps the Quakers' most notable football game was an exhibition game against Japan's Doshisha University Hamburgers in 1989.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] After setting an NCAA Division III record of five consecutive winless seasons, Earlham's football program was suspended starting with the 2019 season.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In May 2020, the college announced suspension of men's and women's golf and tennis teams.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In past years, Earlham was an NAIA member in all sports; they won the NAIA men's soccer national title in 1963.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In the 2010–11 season, the Earlham College Men's Tennis team became the first squad in Earlham history to qualify for the NCAA Div.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] III Championships by winning the Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference Tournament title.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] Earlham's club teams include Ultimate Frisbee, Women's and Men's rugby, the Bike Co-Op, Cheerleaders, Earthquakers (Competitive Dance), Equestrian Program, martial arts groups, Men's Volleyball, and Outdoors Club.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] A $13-million Athletics and Wellness Center opened at the beginning of the Fall 1999 semester.
[src:christopher-benfey/earlham-college] In 2007, Earlham opened its new 2,000-seat Darrell Beane Stadium, with a football field and running track.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson was born in Amherst, Massachusetts to a prominent family.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After studying at the Amherst Academy for seven years, she briefly attended the Mount Holyoke Female Seminary before returning home to Amherst.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although Dickinson was a prolific writer, only 10 of her nearly 1,800 poems were published during her lifetime.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Today her poems are widely regarded as groundbreaking with their use of short acerbic lines, lean descriptions, and slant or off-rhyme.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her poetry primarily deals with nature and mortality.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Few in Dickinson's circle were aware of her writing until after her death, when her younger sister Lavinia discovered the poems in her desk.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] First published as a selection in 1890, edited by Thomas Wentworth Higginson and Mabel Loomis Todd, the poems were significantly altered to fit the prevailing poetic conventions of the time.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Johnson compiled a complete collection of her poetry, "The Poems of Emily Dickinson," was Dickinson's work restored closer to her original intention.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her collection garnered wide recognition for its innovation.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] At least eleven of Dickinson's poems were dedicated to her sister-in-law Susan Huntington Gilbert Dickinson.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Some scholars believe censorship helped to obscure the nature of Emily and Susan's relationship, which has been interpreted as romantic.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Emily Elizabeth Dickinson was born at the family's homestead in Amherst, Massachusetts, on December 10, 1830, into a prominent, but not wealthy, family.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her father, Edward Dickinson, was a lawyer in Amherst and a trustee of Amherst College.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Two hundred years earlier, her patrilineal ancestors had arrived in the New World—in the Puritan Great Migration—where they prospered.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Emily Dickinson's paternal grandfather, Samuel Dickinson, was one of the founders of Amherst College.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1813, he built the Homestead, a large mansion on Amherst's main street, that became the focus of Dickinson family life for the better part of a century.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Samuel Dickinson's eldest son, Edward, was treasurer of Amherst College from 1835 to 1873, served in the Massachusetts House of Representatives (1838–1839; 1873) and the Massachusetts Senate (1842–1843), and represented Massachusetts's 10th congressional district in the 33rd U.S.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] On May 6, 1828, he married Emily Norcross from Monson, Massachusetts.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They had three children: William Austin (1829–1895), known as Austin, Aust or Awe; Emily Elizabeth; and Lavinia Norcross (1833–1899), known as Lavinia or Vinnie.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She was also a distant cousin to Baxter Dickinson and his family, including his grandson, the organist and composer Clarence Dickinson.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson attended primary school in a two-story building on Pleasant Street.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her education was "ambitiously classical for a Victorian girl".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Wanting his children to be well-educated, her father followed their progress even while away on business.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When Dickinson was seven, he wrote home, reminding his children to "keep school, and learn, so as to tell me, when I come home, how many new things you have learned".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] While Dickinson consistently described her father warmly, her correspondence suggests that her mother was regularly cold and aloof.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In a letter to a confidante, Dickinson wrote she "always ran Home to Awe [Austin] when a child, if anything befell me.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] On September 7, 1840, Dickinson and her sister Lavinia started together at Amherst Academy, a former boys' school that had opened to female students just two years earlier.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] At about the same time, her father purchased a house on North Pleasant Street.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's brother Austin later described this large new home as the "mansion" over which he and Dickinson presided as "lord and lady" while their parents were absent.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The house overlooked Amherst's burial ground, described by one local minister as treeless and "forbidding".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson spent seven years at the academy, taking classes in English and classical literature, Latin, botany, geology, history, "mental philosophy," and arithmetic.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Daniel Taggart Fiske, the school's principal at the time, later recalled that Dickinson was "very bright" and "an excellent scholar, of exemplary deportment, faithful in all school duties".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although she took a few terms off due to illness—the longest of which was in 1845–1846, when she was enrolled for only eleven weeks—she enjoyed her strenuous studies, writing to a friend that the academy was "a very fine school".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson was troubled from a young age by the "deepening menace" of death, especially the deaths of those who were close to her.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When Sophia Holland, her second cousin and a close friend, grew ill from typhus and died in April 1844, Dickinson was traumatized.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Recalling the incident two years later, she wrote that "it seemed to me I should die too if I could not be permitted to watch over her or even look at her face." She became so melancholic that her parents sent her to stay with family in Boston to recover.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] With her health and spirits restored, she soon returned to Amherst Academy to continue her studies.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] During this period, she met people who were to become lifelong friends and correspondents, such as Abiah Root, Abby Wood, Jane Humphrey, and Susan Huntington Gilbert, who later married Dickinson's brother Austin.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1845, a religious revival took place in Amherst, resulting in 46 confessions of faith among Dickinson's peers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After her church-going ended, about 1852, she wrote a poem opening: "Some keep the Sabbath going to Church – I keep it, staying at Home".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] During the last year of her stay at the academy, Dickinson became friendly with Leonard Humphrey, its popular new young principal.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After finishing her final term at the Academy on August 10, 1847, Dickinson began attending Mary Lyon's Mount Holyoke Female Seminary, which later became Mount Holyoke College, in South Hadley, about ten miles (16 km) from Amherst.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She stayed at the seminary for only ten months.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although she liked the girls at Mount Holyoke, Dickinson made no lasting friendships there.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The explanations for her brief stay at Mount Holyoke differ considerably: either she was in poor health, her father wanted to have her at home, she rebelled against the evangelical fervor present at the school, she disliked the discipline-minded teachers, or she was simply homesick.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Whatever the reasons for leaving Mount Holyoke, her brother Austin appeared on March 25, 1848, to "bring [her] home at all events".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Back in Amherst, Dickinson occupied her time with household activities.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She took up baking for the family and enjoyed attending local events and activities in the budding college town.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Throughout her early years, Dickinson was influenced mainly by school, church, family, and friends.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When she was eighteen her family befriended a young attorney, Benjamin Franklin Newton.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Over several weeks, they talked about his love of books, and in 1850 he sent her Ralph Waldo Emerson's poems.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Emerson's poems inspired Dickinson with her use of language and that "words had life".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Other friends and family also helped influence her as well, such as Leonard Humphrey who she called her first master before Benjamin Franklin Newton.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Both of their deaths shocked her as they were sudden.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Another person in her life that influenced her was Susan Gilbert, her friend and sister-in law, as they both shared a library together.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They both highlighted and underlined passages from books that interested them the most.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Henry Vaughan Emmons was another friend with whom she exchanged letters that expanded her interest in reading as well as access to books that would not have been allowed in her home.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] During her school years, she was reported to have taken a liking to her teachers, often writing positively about them in her letters to her friends.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She discussed books with various students and teachers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They discussed books by Thomas De Quincey, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Thomas Carlyle and Jean Paul Richter.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Outside of these discussions, she had a fascination with botany.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It delighted her, and she ended up keeping her herbarium by her botany textbook throughout her life.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's love of flowers and plants is emphasised throughout her letters and poetry.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] However, due to long periods away from her home and family, Emily recalled school being a lonely and isolated place for her.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Strong she wrote: "I was very homesick for a few days, and it seemed to be I could not live here [Mt.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] But I am now contented and quite happy, if I can be happy when absent from my dear home and friends.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] You may laugh at the idea that I cannot be happy when away from home, but you must remember that I have a very dear home." In Dickinson's poems, isolation is a running theme relating to her feelings of being separated from society within her suffering.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Ford recalls groups she had with Emily Dickinson over their school years: "we met to discuss books.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's family were Calvinists and they practiced daily religious observances.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When she was 13, her father gave her a Bible to study.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She often used quotes from the Bible in her poems and letters to her friends, as a way to raise unanswerable questions rather than to resolve them.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] For her, the Bible was a rhetoric manual.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She was also influenced by many writers that she had encountered throughout her early life.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In her letter to Higginson, she wrote "For Poets I have Keats, and Mr and Mrs Browning.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] For prose, Mr Ruskin, Sir Thomas Brown, and the Revelations".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson quoted Keats regularly in her letters to her friends, and she was inspired by his thoughts on aspects like morality and fame.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She regularly quoted Shakespeare in her letters to Abiah Root, particularly *Macbeth*, in the years 1845 and 1850.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her family had books written by the Brontës and she wrote about them in a few letters to her friends; one of her poems is to commemorate the death of Charlotte Brontë.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson used her writing to experiment and take risks, often not conforming to specific poetry rules.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It has been reported that most of Emily Dickinson's poetry was written during the period of the American Civil War.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The war, along with the rest of the nineteenth-century world, inspired Dickinson's poetry as she wrote about its battles, chaos, and the courage of the soldiers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Often she reflected on these happenings in comparison to her views on war and death, such as in the poems "When I was small, a Woman died", "My Portion is Defeat- today-", and "My Triumph lasted till the Drums".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] With the Civil War happening during her time, experiencing the death of her friends and family as well as her close observations of nature and its cycle, Dickinson drew on these as inspiration for her poems and musings.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In early 1850, Dickinson wrote, "Amherst is alive with fun this winter ...
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her high spirits soon turned to melancholy after another death.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The Amherst Academy principal, Leonard Humphrey, died suddenly of "brain congestion" at age 25.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In the 1850s, Dickinson's strongest and most affectionate relationship was with her sister-in-law, Susan Gilbert, who married Dickinson's brother Austin in 1856 after a four-year courtship, though their marriage was not a happy one.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Edward Dickinson built a house for Austin which Gilbert named the Evergreens, a stand of which was located on the west side of the Homestead.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson eventually sent Susan Gilbert over three hundred letters, more than to any other correspondent, over the course of their relationship.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Susan was supportive of the poet, playing the role of "most beloved friend, influence, muse, and adviser" whose editorial suggestions Dickinson sometimes followed.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1998, *The New York Times* reported on a study in which infrared technology revealed that certain poems of Dickinson's had been deliberately censored to exclude the name "Susan".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's dedications of 11 poems to Susan Gilbert were deliberately censored, presumably by Todd, Gilbert's romantic rival.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The notion of a "cruel" Susan – as promoted by Todd – has been questioned, most especially by Dickinson's nieces and nephews (Susan and Austin's surviving children), with whom Dickinson was close.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Many scholars interpret the relationship between Emily and Susan as a romantic one.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The relationship between Emily and Susan is portrayed in the film *Wild Nights with Emily* and explored in the TV series *Dickinson*.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Until 1855, Dickinson had not strayed far from Amherst.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] That spring, accompanied by her mother and sister, she took one of her longest and farthest trips away from home.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] First, they spent three weeks in Washington, where her father was representing Massachusetts in Congress, then travelled to Philadelphia for two weeks to visit family.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] While in Philadelphia, she met Charles Wadsworth, a famous minister of the Arch Street Presbyterian Church, with whom she forged a strong friendship that lasted until he died in 1882.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Despite seeing him only twice after 1855 (he moved to San Francisco in 1862), she variously referred to him as "my Philadelphia", "my Clergyman", "my dearest earthly friend" and "my Shepherd from 'Little Girl'hood".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] From the mid-1850s, Dickinson's mother became effectively bedridden with chronic illnesses until she died in 1882.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Writing to a friend in the summer of 1858, Dickinson said she would visit if she could leave "home, or mother.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] I do not go out at all, lest father will come and miss me, or miss some little act, which I might forget, should I run away – Mother is much as usual.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] As her mother continued to decline, Dickinson's domestic responsibilities weighed more heavily upon her and she confined herself within the Homestead.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Forty years later, Lavinia said that because their mother was chronically ill, one of the daughters had to remain always with her.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson took this role as her own, and "finding the life with her books and nature so congenial, continued to live it".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Withdrawing more and more from the outside world, Dickinson began in the summer of 1858 what would be her lasting legacy.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Reviewing poems she had written previously, she began making clean copies of her work, assembling carefully pieced-together manuscript books.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The forty fascicles she created from 1858 to 1865 eventually held nearly eight hundred poems.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] No one was aware of the existence of these books until after her death.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In the late 1850s, the Dickinsons befriended Samuel Bowles, the owner and editor-in-chief of the *Springfield Republican*, and his wife Mary.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They visited the Dickinsons regularly for years to come.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] During this time, Dickinson sent him over three dozen letters and nearly fifty poems.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Their friendship brought out some of her most intense writing and Bowles published a few of her poems in his journal.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It was from 1858 to 1861 that Dickinson is believed to have written a trio of letters that have been called "The Master Letters".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] These three letters, drafted to an unknown man simply referred to as "Master", continue to be the subject of speculation and contention amongst scholars.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson also became friends with *Springfield Republican* Assistant Editor J.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Holland and his wife and frequently corresponded with them.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She was a guest at their Springfield home on numerous occasions.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson was a poet "influenced by transcendentalism and dark romanticism," and her work bridged "the gap to Realism." Of the ten poems published in her lifetime, the *Springfield Republican* published five (all unsigned), with Sam Bowles and Josiah Holland as editors, between 1852 and 1866.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Some scholars believe that Bowles promoted her the most; Dickinson wrote letters and sent her poems to both men.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The first half of the 1860s, after she had largely withdrawn from social life, proved to be Dickinson's most productive writing period.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Modern scholars and researchers are divided as to the cause for Dickinson's withdrawal and extreme seclusion.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] While she was diagnosed as having "nervous prostration" by a physician during her lifetime, some today believe she may have suffered from illnesses as various as agoraphobia and epilepsy.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In April 1862, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, a literary critic, radical abolitionist, and ex-minister, wrote a lead piece for *The Atlantic Monthly* titled, "Letter to a Young Contributor".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Higginson's essay, in which he urged aspiring writers to "charge your style with life", contained practical advice for those wishing to break into print.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's decision to contact Higginson suggests that by 1862 she was contemplating publication and that it may have become increasingly difficult to write poetry without an audience.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] This highly nuanced and largely theatrical letter was unsigned, but she had included her name on a card and enclosed it in an envelope, along with four of her poems.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] He praised her work but suggested that she delay publishing until she had written longer, being unaware she had already appeared in print.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She assured him that publishing was as foreign to her "as Firmament to Fin", but also proposed that "If fame belonged to me, I could not escape her".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson delighted in dramatic self-characterization and mystery in her letters to Higginson.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She said of herself, "I am small, like the wren, and my hair is bold, like the chestnut bur, and my eyes like the sherry in the glass that the guest leaves." She stressed her solitary nature, saying her only real companions were the hills, the sundown, and her dog, Carlo.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She mentioned that whereas her mother did not "care for Thought", her father bought her books, but begged her "not to read them – because he fears they joggle the Mind".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson valued his advice, going from calling him "Mr.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Higginson" to "Dear friend" as well as signing her letters, "Your Gnome" and "Your Scholar".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] His interest in her work certainly provided great moral support.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Many years later, Dickinson told Higginson that he had saved her life in 1862.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They corresponded until her death, but her difficulty in expressing her literary needs and a reluctance to enter into a cooperative exchange left Higginson nonplussed.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] He did not press her to publish in subsequent correspondence.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's own ambivalence on the matter militated against the likelihood of publication.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Literary critic Edmund Wilson, in his review of Civil War literature, surmised that "with encouragement, she would certainly have published".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In direct opposition to the immense productivity that she displayed in the early 1860s, Dickinson wrote fewer poems in 1866.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Beset with personal loss as well as loss of domestic help, Dickinson may have been too overcome to keep up her previous level of writing.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Carlo died during this time after having provided sixteen years of companionship.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although the household servant of nine years, Margaret O'Brien, had married and left the Homestead that same year, it was not until 1869 that the Dickinsons brought in another permanent household servant, Margaret Maher, to replace their former maid-of-all-work.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Emily once again was responsible for the kitchen, including cooking and cleaning up, as well as the baking at which she excelled.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Around this time, Dickinson's behavior began to change.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She did not leave the Homestead unless it was absolutely necessary, and as early as 1867, she began to talk to visitors from the other side of a door rather than speaking to them face to face.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She acquired local notoriety; she was rarely seen, and when she was, she was usually clothed in white.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's one surviving article of clothing is a white cotton dress, possibly sewn circa 1878–1882.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Few of the locals who exchanged messages with Dickinson during her last fifteen years ever saw her in person.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Austin and his family began to protect Dickinson's privacy, deciding that she was not to be a subject of discussion with outsiders.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Despite her physical seclusion, Dickinson was socially active and expressive through what makes up two-thirds of her surviving notes and letters.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When visitors came to either the Homestead or the Evergreens, she would often leave or send over small gifts of poems or flowers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson also had a good rapport with the children in her life.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When Higginson urged her to come to Boston in 1868 so they could formally meet for the first time, she declined, writing: "Could it please your convenience to come so far as Amherst I should be very glad, but I do not cross my Father's ground to any House or town".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It was not until he came to Amherst in 1870 that they met.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Scholar Judith Farr notes that Dickinson, during her lifetime, "was known more widely as a gardener, perhaps, than as a poet".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson studied botany from the age of nine and, along with her sister, tended the garden at Homestead.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] During her lifetime, she assembled a collection of pressed plants in a sixty-six-page leather-bound herbarium.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It contained 424 pressed flower specimens that she collected, classified, and labeled using the Linnaean system.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The Homestead garden was well known and admired locally in its time.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It has not survived, but efforts to revive it have begun.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson kept no garden notebooks or plant lists, but a clear impression can be formed from the letters and recollections of friends and family.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Her niece, Martha Dickinson Bianchi, remembered "carpets of lily-of-the-valley and pansies, platoons of sweetpeas, hyacinths, enough in May to give all the bees of summer dyspepsia.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] There were ribbons of peony hedges and drifts of daffodils in season, marigolds to distraction—a butterfly utopia".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In particular, Dickinson cultivated scented exotic flowers, writing that she "could inhabit the Spice Isles merely by crossing the dining room to the conservatory, where the plants hang in baskets".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson would often send her friends bunches of flowers with verses attached, but "they valued the posy more than the poetry".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] On June 16, 1874, while in Boston, Edward Dickinson suffered a stroke and died.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] When the simple funeral was held in the Homestead's entrance hall, Dickinson stayed in her room with the door cracked open; she didn't attend the memorial service on June 28.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She wrote to Higginson that her father's "Heart was pure and terrible and I think no other like it exists." A year later, on June 15, 1875, Dickinson's mother also suffered a stroke, which produced a partial lateral paralysis and impaired memory.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Lamenting her mother's increasing physical as well as mental demands, Dickinson wrote that "Home is so far from Home".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Otis Phillips Lord, an elderly judge on the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court from Salem, in 1872 or 1873 became an acquaintance of Dickinson's.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After the death of Lord's wife in 1877, his friendship with Dickinson probably became a late-life romance, though as their letters were destroyed, this is surmised.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson found a kindred soul in Lord, especially in terms of shared literary interests.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The few letters that survived contain multiple quotations of Shakespeare's work, including the plays *Othello*, *Antony and Cleopatra*, *Hamlet* and *King Lear*.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1880 he gave her Mary Cowden Clarke's *Complete Concordance to Shakespeare* (1877).
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson wrote, "While others go to Church, I go to mine, for are you not my Church, and have we not a Hymn that no one knows but us?" She referred to him as "My lovely Salem" and they wrote to each other religiously every Sunday.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson looked forward to this day greatly; a surviving fragment of a letter written by her states that "Tuesday is a deeply depressed Day".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After being critically ill for several years, Judge Lord died in March 1884.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson referred to him as "our latest Lost".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Two years before this, on April 1, 1882, Dickinson's "Shepherd from 'Little Girl'hood", Charles Wadsworth, also had died after a long illness.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although she continued to write in her last years, Dickinson stopped editing and organizing her poems.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She also exacted a promise from her sister Lavinia to burn her papers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Lavinia, who never married, remained at the Homestead until her own death in 1899.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The 1880s were a difficult time for the remaining Dickinsons.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Irreconcilably alienated from his wife, Austin fell in love in 1882 with Mabel Loomis Todd, an Amherst College faculty wife who had recently moved to the area.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Todd never met Dickinson but was intrigued by her, referring to her as "a lady whom the people call the *Myth*".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Austin distanced himself from his family as his affair continued and his wife became sick with grief.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson's mother died on November 14, 1882.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Five weeks later, Dickinson wrote, "We were never intimate ... while she was our Mother – but Mines in the same Ground meet by tunneling and when she became our Child, the Affection came." The next year, Austin and Susan's third and youngest child, Gilbert—Emily's favorite—died of typhoid fever.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] As death succeeded death, Dickinson found her world upended.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In late 1884, she wrote, "The Dyings have been too deep for me, and before I could raise my Heart from one, another has come." That summer, she had seen "a great darkness coming" and fainted while baking in the kitchen.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She remained unconscious late into the night and weeks of ill health followed.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] On November 30, 1885, her feebleness and other symptoms were so worrying that Austin canceled a trip to Boston.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She was confined to her bed for a few months, but managed to send a final burst of letters in the spring.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] What is thought to be her last letter was sent to her cousins, Louise and Frances Norcross, and simply read: "Little Cousins, Called Back.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] On May 15, 1886, after several days of worsening symptoms, Dickinson died at the age of 55.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Austin wrote in his diary that "the day was awful ... she ceased to breathe that terrible breathing just before the [afternoon] whistle sounded for six." Dickinson's chief physician gave the cause of death as Bright's disease and its duration as two and a half years.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Lavinia and Austin asked Susan to wash Dickinson's body upon her death.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson was buried, laid in a white coffin with vanilla-scented heliotrope, a lady's slipper orchid, and a "knot of blue field violets" placed about it.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The funeral service, held in the Homestead's library, was simple and short; Higginson, who had met her only twice, read "No Coward Soul Is Mine", a poem by Emily Brontë that had been a favorite of Dickinson's.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] At Dickinson's request, her "coffin [was] not driven but carried through fields of buttercups" for burial in the family plot at West Cemetery on Triangle Street.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Despite Dickinson's prolific writing, only ten poems and a letter were published during her lifetime.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After her younger sister Lavinia discovered the collection of nearly 1,800 poems, Dickinson's first volume was published four years after her death.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Johnson published Dickinson's *Complete Poems* in 1955, Dickinson's poems were considerably edited and altered from their manuscript versions.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Since 1890 Dickinson has remained continuously in print.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] A few of Dickinson's poems appeared in Samuel Bowles' *Springfield Republican* between 1858 and 1868.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They were published anonymously and heavily edited, with conventionalized punctuation and formal titles.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The first poem, "Nobody knows this little rose", may have been published without Dickinson's permission.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The *Republican* also published "A Narrow Fellow in the Grass" as "The Snake", "Safe in their Alabaster Chambers –" as "The Sleeping", and "Blazing in the Gold and quenching in Purple" as "Sunset".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The poem "I taste a liquor never brewed –" is an example of the edited versions; the last two lines in the first stanza were completely rewritten.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1864, several poems were altered and published in *Drum Beat*, to raise funds for medical care for Union soldiers in the war.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Another appeared in April 1864 in the *Brooklyn Daily Union*.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In the 1870s, Higginson showed Dickinson's poems to Helen Hunt Jackson, who had coincidentally been at the academy with Dickinson when they were girls.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Jackson was deeply involved in the publishing world, and managed to convince Dickinson to publish her poem "Success is counted sweetest" anonymously in a volume called *A Masque of Poets*.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The poem, however, was altered to agree with contemporary taste.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] It was the last poem published during Dickinson's lifetime.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] After Dickinson's death, Lavinia Dickinson kept her promise and burned most of the poet's correspondence.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Significantly though, Dickinson had left no instructions about the 40 notebooks and loose sheets gathered in a locked chest.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Lavinia recognized the poems' worth and became obsessed with seeing them published.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] She turned first to her brother's wife and then to Mabel Loomis Todd, his lover, for assistance.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] A feud ensued, with the manuscripts divided between the Todd and Dickinson houses, preventing the complete publication of Dickinson's poetry for more than half a century.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The first volume of Dickinson's *Poems,* edited jointly by Mabel Loomis Todd and T.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Although Todd claimed that only essential changes were made, the poems were extensively edited to match punctuation and capitalization to late 19th-century standards, with occasional rewordings to reduce Dickinson's obliquity.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The first 115-poem volume was a critical and financial success, going through eleven printings in two years.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] *Poems: Second Series* followed in 1891, running to five editions by 1893; a third series appeared in 1896.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] One reviewer, in 1892, wrote: "The world will not rest satisfied till every scrap of her writings, letters as well as literature, has been published".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Nearly a dozen new editions of Dickinson's poetry, whether containing previously unpublished or newly edited poems, were published between 1914 and 1945.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Martha Dickinson Bianchi, the daughter of Susan and Austin Dickinson, published collections of her aunt's poetry based on the manuscripts held by her family, whereas Mabel Loomis Todd's daughter, Millicent Todd Bingham, published collections based on the manuscripts held by her mother.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] These competing editions of Dickinson's poetry, often differing in order and structure, ensured that the poet's work was in the public's eye.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] The first scholarly publication came in 1955 with a completely new three-volume set edited by Thomas H.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Forming the basis of later Dickinson scholarship, Johnson's variorum brought all of Dickinson's known poems together for the first time.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Johnson's goal was to present the poems very nearly as Dickinson had left them in her manuscripts.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] They were untitled, only numbered in an approximate chronological sequence, strewn with dashes and irregularly capitalized, and often extremely elliptical in their language.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Three years later, Johnson edited and published, along with Theodora Ward, a complete collection of Dickinson's letters, also presented in three volumes.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] In 1981, *The Manuscript Books of Emily Dickinson* was published.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Using the physical evidence of the original papers, the poems were intended to be published in their original order for the first time.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Franklin relied on smudge marks, needle punctures and other clues to reassemble the poet's packets.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Since then, many critics have argued for thematic unity in these small collections, believing the ordering of the poems to be more than chronological or convenient.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p01] Dickinson biographer Alfred Habegger wrote in *My Wars Are Laid Away in Books: The Life of Emily Dickinson* (2001) that "The consequences of the poet's failure to disseminate her work in a faithful and orderly manner are still very much with us".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson's poems generally fall into three distinct periods, the works in each period having certain general characters in common.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The extensive use of dashes and unconventional capitalization in Dickinson's manuscripts, and the idiosyncratic vocabulary and imagery, combine to create a body of work that is "far more various in its styles and forms than is commonly supposed".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson avoids pentameter, opting more generally for trimeter, tetrameter and, less often, dimeter.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Sometimes her use of these meters is regular, but oftentimes it is irregular.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The regular form that she most often employs is the ballad stanza, a traditional form that is divided into quatrains, using tetrameter for the first and third lines and trimeter for the second and fourth, while rhyming the second and fourth lines (ABCB).
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Though Dickinson often uses perfect rhymes for lines two and four, she also makes frequent use of slant rhyme.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In some of her poems, she varies the meter from the traditional ballad stanza by using trimeter for lines one, two and four; while using tetrameter for only line three.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Since many of her poems were written in traditional ballad stanzas with ABCB rhyme schemes, some of these poems can be sung to fit the melodies of popular folk songs and hymns that also use the common meter, employing alternating lines of iambic tetrameter and iambic trimeter.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Late 20th-century scholars are "deeply interested" in Dickinson's highly individual use of punctuation and lineation (line lengths and line breaks).
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] As Farr points out, "snakes instantly notice you"; Dickinson's version captures the "breathless immediacy" of the encounter; and *The Republican*'s punctuation renders "her lines more commonplace".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] With the increasingly close focus on Dickinson's structures and syntax has come a growing appreciation that they are "aesthetically based".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Although Johnson's landmark 1955 edition of poems was relatively unaltered from the original, later scholars critiqued it for deviating from the style and layout of Dickinson's manuscripts.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Meaningful distinctions, these scholars assert, can be drawn from varying lengths and angles of dash, and differing arrangements of text on the page.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Several volumes have attempted to render Dickinson's handwritten dashes using many typographic symbols of varying length and angle.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Franklin's 1998 variorum edition of the poems provided alternate wordings to those chosen by Johnson, in a more limited editorial intervention.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Franklin also used typeset dashes of varying length to approximate the manuscripts' dashes more closely.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson left no formal statement of her aesthetic intentions and, because of the variety of her themes, her work does not fit conveniently into any genre.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] She has been regarded, alongside Emerson (whose poems Dickinson admired), as a Transcendentalist.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] However, Farr disagrees with this analysis, saying that Dickinson's "relentlessly measuring mind ... deflates the airy elevation of the Transcendental".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Apart from the major themes discussed below, Dickinson's poetry frequently uses humor, puns, irony and satire.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The surge of posthumous publication gave Dickinson's poetry its first public exposure.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Backed by Higginson and with a favorable notice from William Dean Howells, an editor of *Harper's Magazine*, the poetry received mixed reviews after it was first published in 1890.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Higginson himself stated in his preface to the first edition of Dickinson's published work that the poetry's quality "is that of extraordinary grasp and insight", albeit "without the proper control and chastening" that the experience of publishing during her lifetime might have conferred.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] His judgment that her opus was "incomplete and unsatisfactory" would be echoed in the essays of the New Critics in the 1930s.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Maurice Thompson, who was literary editor of *The Independent* for twelve years, noted in 1891 that her poetry had "a strange mixture of rare individuality and originality".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Some critics hailed Dickinson's effort but disapproved of her unusual non-traditional style.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Andrew Lang, a British writer, dismissed Dickinson's work, stating that "if poetry is to exist at all, it really must have form and grammar, and must rhyme when it professes to rhyme.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The wisdom of the ages and the nature of man insist on so much".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Thomas Bailey Aldrich, a poet and novelist, equally dismissed Dickinson's poetic technique in *The Atlantic Monthly* in January 1892: "It is plain that Miss Dickinson possessed an extremely unconventional and grotesque fancy.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] She was deeply tinged by the mysticism of Blake, and strongly influenced by the mannerism of Emerson ...
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] But the incoherence and formlessness of her—versicles are fatal ... an eccentric, dreamy, half-educated recluse in an out-of-the-way New England village (or anywhere else) cannot with impunity set at defiance the laws of gravitation and grammar".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Critical attention to Dickinson's poetry was meager from 1897 to the early 1920s.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] By the start of the 20th century, interest in her poetry became broader in scope and some critics began to consider Dickinson as essentially modern.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Rather than seeing Dickinson's poetic styling as a result of a lack of knowledge or skill, modern critics believed the irregularities were consciously artistic.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In a 1915 essay, Elizabeth Shepley Sergeant called the poet's inspiration "daring" and named her "one of the rarest flowers the sterner New England land ever bore".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] With the growing popularity of modernist poetry in the 1920s, Dickinson's failure to conform to 19th-century poetic form was no longer surprising nor distasteful to new generations of readers.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson was suddenly referred to by various critics as a great woman poet, and a cult following began to form.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In the 1930s, a number of the New Critics—among them R.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Blackmur, Allen Tate, Cleanth Brooks and Yvor Winters—appraised the significance of Dickinson's poetry.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] As critic Roland Hagenbüchle pointed out, their "affirmative and prohibitive tenets turned out to be of special relevance to Dickinson scholarship".
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Blackmur, in an attempt to focus and clarify the major claims for and against the poet's greatness, wrote in a landmark 1937 critical essay: "... she was a private poet who wrote as indefatigably as some women cook or knit.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Her gift for words and the cultural predicament of her time drove her to poetry instead of antimacassars ...
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The second wave of feminism created greater cultural sympathy for her as a female poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In the first collection of critical essays on Dickinson from a feminist perspective, she is heralded as the greatest woman poet in the English language.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Biographers and theorists of the past tended to separate Dickinson's roles as a woman and a poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Adrienne Rich theorized in *Vesuvius at Home: The Power of Emily Dickinson* (1976) that Dickinson's identity as a woman poet brought her power: "[she] chose her seclusion, knowing she was exceptional and knowing what she needed ...
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Some scholars question the poet's sexuality, theorizing that the numerous letters and poems that were dedicated to Susan Gilbert Dickinson indicate a lesbian romance, and speculating about how this may have influenced her poetry.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Critics such as John Cody, Lillian Faderman, Vivian R.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Pollak, Paula Bennett, Judith Farr, Ellen Louise Hart, and Martha Nell Smith have argued that Susan was the central erotic relationship in Dickinson's life.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In the early 20th century, Martha Dickinson Bianchi and Millicent Todd Bingham kept the achievement of Emily Dickinson alive.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Bianchi promoted Dickinson's poetic achievement.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Bianchi inherited The Evergreens as well as the copyright for her aunt's poetry from her parents, publishing works such as *Emily Dickinson Face to Face* and *Letters of Emily Dickinson*, which stoked public curiosity about her aunt.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Bianchi's books perpetrated legends about her aunt in the context of family tradition, personal recollection and correspondence.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In contrast, Millicent Todd Bingham's took a more objective and realistic approach to the poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Emily Dickinson is now considered a powerful and persistent figure in American culture.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Although much of the early reception concentrated on Dickinson's eccentric and secluded nature, she has become widely acknowledged as an innovative, proto-modernist poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Eliot, and Hart Crane as a major American poet, and in 1994 listed her among the 26 central writers of Western civilization.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson is taught in American literature and poetry classes in the United States from middle school to college.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Her poetry is frequently anthologized and has been used as text for art songs by composers such as Aaron Copland, Nick Peros, John Adams and Michael Tilson Thomas.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Several schools have been established in her name; for example, Emily Dickinson Elementary Schools exist in Bozeman, Montana; Redmond, Washington; and New York City.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] A few literary journals—including *The Emily Dickinson Journal*, the official publication of the Emily Dickinson International Society—have been founded to examine her work.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The Emily Dickinson International Society was founded in 1988, eight years after an Emily Dickinson Society was formed in Japan in 1980.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] An 8-cent commemorative stamp in honor of Dickinson, designed by Bernard Fuchs, was issued by the United States Postal Service on August 28, 1971, as the second stamp in the "American Poet" series.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson was inducted into the National Women's Hall of Fame in 1973.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] A one-woman play titled *The Belle of Amherst* appeared on Broadway in 1976, winning several awards; it was later adapted for television.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Dickinson's herbarium, which is now held in the Houghton Library at Harvard University, was published in 2006 as *Emily Dickinson's Herbarium* by Harvard University Press.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The original work was compiled by Dickinson during her years at Amherst Academy, and consists of 424 pressed specimens of plants arranged on 66 pages of a bound album.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] A digital facsimile of the herbarium is available online.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The Archives and Special Collections at Amherst College has substantial holdings of Dickinson's manuscripts and letters as well as a lock of Dickinson's hair and the original of the only positively identified image of the poet.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] In 1965, in recognition of Dickinson's growing stature as a poet, the Homestead was purchased by Amherst College.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] It opened to the public for tours, and also served as a faculty residence for many years.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] The Emily Dickinson Museum was created in 2003 when ownership of the Evergreens, which had been occupied by Dickinson family heirs until 1988, was transferred to the college.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Emily Dickinson's life and works have been the source of inspiration to artists, particularly to feminist-oriented artists, of a variety of mediums.
[src:christopher-benfey/emily-dickinson-p02] Emily Dickinson's poetry has been translated into languages including French, Spanish, Mandarin Chinese, Persian, Kurdish, Turkish, Georgian, Swedish, and Russian.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Born in the Colony of Virginia, Washington became the commander of the Virginia Regiment during the French and Indian War from 1754 to 1763.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He was later elected to the Virginia House of Burgesses, and opposed the perceived oppression of the American colonists by the British Crown.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] When the American Revolutionary War against the British began in 1775, Washington was appointed commander-in-chief of the Continental Army.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He directed a poorly organized and equipped force against disciplined British troops.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington and his army achieved an early victory at the Siege of Boston in March 1776 but were forced to retreat from New York City in November.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River and won the battles of Trenton in late 1776 and of Princeton in early 1777, then lost the battles of Brandywine and Germantown later that year.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He faced criticism of his command, low troop morale, and a lack of provisions for his forces as the war continued.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Ultimately Washington led a combined French and American force to a decisive victory over the British at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In the resulting Treaty of Paris in 1783, the British acknowledged the sovereign independence of the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington then served as president of the Constitutional Convention in 1787, which drafted the current Constitution of the United States.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington was unanimously elected the first U.S. president by the Electoral College in 1788 and 1792.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He established a strong, well-financed national government while remaining impartial in the fierce rivalry that emerged within his cabinet between Thomas Jefferson and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] During the French Revolution, he adopted a policy of neutrality while supporting the Jay Treaty with Britain.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington set enduring precedents for the office of president, including republicanism, a peaceful transfer of power, the use of the title "Mr.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] His 1796 farewell address became a preeminent statement on republicanism: Washington wrote about the importance of national unity and the dangers that regionalism, partisanship, and foreign influence pose to it.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] As a planter of tobacco and wheat at Mount Vernon, Washington owned many slaves.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He began opposing slavery near the end of his life, and provided in his will for the eventual manumission of his slaves.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington's image is an icon of American culture and he has been extensively memorialized.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] His namesakes include the national capital and the State of Washington.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In both popular and scholarly polls, he is consistently considered one of the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] George Washington was born on February 22, 1732, at Popes Creek in Westmoreland County, Virginia.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He was the first of six children of Augustine and Mary Ball Washington.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] His father was a justice of the peace and a prominent public figure who had four additional children from his first marriage to Jane Butler.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington was not close to his father and rarely mentioned him in later years; he had a fractious relationship with his mother.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Among his siblings, he was particularly close to his older half-brother Lawrence.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The family moved to a plantation on Little Hunting Creek in 1735 before settling at Ferry Farm near Fredericksburg, Virginia, in 1738.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] When Augustine died in 1743, Washington inherited Ferry Farm and ten slaves; Lawrence inherited Little Hunting Creek and renamed it Mount Vernon.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Because of his father's death, Washington did not have the formal education his elder half-brothers had received at Appleby Grammar School in England; he instead attended the Lower Church School in Hartfield.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He learned mathematics and land surveying, and became a talented draftsman and mapmaker.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] By early adulthood, he was writing with what his biographer Ron Chernow described as "considerable force" and "precision".
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] As a teenager, Washington compiled over a hundred rules for social interaction styled *The Rules of Civility*, copied from an English translation of a French guidebook.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington often visited Belvoir, the plantation of William Fairfax, Lawrence's father-in-law, and Mount Vernon.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Fairfax became Washington's patron and surrogate father.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In 1748, Washington spent a month with a team surveying Fairfax's Shenandoah Valley property.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The following year, he received a surveyor's license from the College of William & Mary.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Even though Washington had not served the customary apprenticeship, Thomas Fairfax (William's cousin) appointed him surveyor of Culpeper County, Virginia.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington took his oath of office on July 20, 1749, and resigned in 1750.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] By 1752, he had bought almost 1,500 acres (600 ha) in the Shenandoah Valley and owned 2,315 acres (937 ha).
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In 1751, Washington left mainland North America for the first and only time, when he accompanied Lawrence to Barbados, hoping the climate would cure his brother's tuberculosis.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington contracted smallpox during the trip, which left his face slightly scarred and provided immunity against future infection.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Lawrence died in 1752, and Washington leased Mount Vernon from his widow, Ann; he inherited it outright after her death in 1761.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The Barbados journey exposed Washington to the wider British Atlantic world and to aspects of plantation society and imperial administration beyond Virginia.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Lawrence Washington's service as adjutant general of the Virginia militia inspired George to seek a militia commission.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Virginia's lieutenant governor, Robert Dinwiddie, appointed Washington as a major and commander of one of the four militia districts.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The British and French were competing for control of the Ohio River Valley: the British were constructing forts along the river, and the French between the river and Lake Erie.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In October 1753, Dinwiddie appointed Washington as a special envoy to demand the French forces vacate land that was claimed by the British.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington was also directed to make peace with the Haudenosaunee (Iroquois) Confederacy and to gather intelligence about the French forces.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington met with Haudenosaunee leader Tanacharison at Logstown.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington said that at this meeting Tanacharison named him Conotocaurius.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] This name, meaning "devourer of villages", had previously been given to his great-grandfather John Washington in the late 17th century by the Susquehannock.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington's party reached the Ohio River in November 1753 and was intercepted by a French patrol.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The party was escorted to Fort Le Boeuf, where Washington was received in a friendly manner.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He delivered the British demand to vacate to the French commander Jacques Legardeur de Saint-Pierre, but the French refused to leave.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Saint-Pierre gave Washington his official answer after a few days' delay, as well as food and winter clothing for his party's journey back to Virginia.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington completed the precarious mission in difficult winter conditions, achieving a measure of distinction when his report was published in Virginia and London.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In February 1754, Dinwiddie promoted Washington to lieutenant colonel and second-in-command of the 300-strong Virginia Regiment, with orders to confront the French at the Forks of the Ohio.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington set out with half the regiment in April and was soon aware that a French force of 1,000 had begun construction of Fort Duquesne there.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In May, having established a defensive position at Great Meadows, Washington learned that the French had made camp seven miles (11 km) away; he decided to take the offensive.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The French detachment proved to be only about 50 men, so on May 28 Washington commanded an ambush.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] His small force of Virginians and Indian allies killed the French, including their commander Joseph Coulon de Jumonville, who had been carrying a diplomatic message for the British.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The French later found their countrymen dead and scalped, blaming Washington, who had retreated to Fort Necessity.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The rest of the Virginia Regiment joined Washington the following month with news that he had been promoted to the rank of colonel and given command of the full regiment.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] They were reinforced by an independent company of a hundred South Carolinians led by Captain James Mackay; his royal commission outranked Washington's and a conflict of command ensued.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] On July 3, 900 French soldiers attacked Fort Necessity, and the ensuing battle ended in Washington's surrender.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington did not speak French, but signed a surrender document in which he unwittingly took responsibility for "assassinating" Jumonville, later blaming the translator for not properly translating it.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The Virginia Regiment was divided and Washington was offered a captaincy in one of the newly formed regiments.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] He refused, as it would have been a demotion—the British had ordered that "colonials" could not be ranked any higher than captain—and instead resigned his commission.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] The Jumonville affair became the incident which ignited the French and Indian War.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] In 1755, Washington volunteered as an aide to General Edward Braddock, who led a British expedition to expel the French from Fort Duquesne and the Ohio Country.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] On Washington's recommendation, Braddock split the army into one main column and a smaller "flying column".
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Washington was suffering from severe dysentery so did not initially travel with the expedition forces.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] When he rejoined Braddock at Monongahela, still very ill, the French and their Indian allies ambushed the divided army.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Two-thirds of the British force became casualties in the ensuing Battle of the Monongahela, and Braddock was killed.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] Under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Thomas Gage, Washington rallied the survivors and formed a rear guard, allowing the remnants of the force to retreat.
[src:christopher-benfey/george-washington-p01] During the engagement, Washington had two horses shot out from under him, and his hat and coat were pierced by bullets.
